{"title_page": "Bakewell Town FC", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Bakewell Town F.C.\n| image = [[File:Bakewell Town FC Crest.png|thumb|Bakewell Town FC Crest]]\n| fullname = Bakewell Town Football Club\n| founded = 1883\n| ground = Bakewell Recreation Ground\n| manager = Ross Davies\n| website = https://www.pitchero.com/clubs/bakewelltownfc/\n| pattern_b1 = _lightbluestripes\n| shorts1 = 33CEFF\n| socks1 = 33CEFF\n}}'''Bakewell Town Football Club''' is a [[Association football|football]] club based in [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derbyshire|title=Derbyshire|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2020}}, England. They are current members of the [[Central Midlands Football League]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centralmidlandsleague.pitchero.com/|title=Central Midlands Football League|website=centralmidlandsleague.pitchero.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Division One South\n\n== History ==\nThe club were pitched at the inaugural meeting held at the [[Midland Hotel, Derby|Midland Hotel]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hallmarkhotels.co.uk/hotels/hallmark-hotel-derby-midland/|title=Midland Hotel|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in [[Derby]] in 1883 as Bakewell FC in which an Association of [[Derbyshire]]<ref name=\":0\" /> Football Clubs was formed & called the [[Derbyshire County Football Association|Derbyshire Football Association]].\n\nThe first known proof of organised football being played in the town shows photos which date back to circa 1890's.\n\nBakewell Town had been hovering in all three of the [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope Valley]] Divisions in the 80s-90's as an influx of interest for football in the Town after [[England national football team|England]]\u2019s near miss in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]] resulted in plenty of playing resource as three teams Bakewell FC, Bakewell Wheatsheaf FC 1st & Bakewell Town Reserves met at the Manners Public House Hotel to broker a merger at the end of the 99/00 season, this saw two teams, a First Team and Reserve side playing under the banner of Bakewell Town FC formed with one Team residing in the top [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope Valley]] Premier Division and the other in the third tier B Division, this structure is still in order to this day.\n\nAfter several years hovering between the Premier and A Division of the HVL structure the 1st Team had a huge bout of success as they first secured the A Division Cup and followed that a year later winning the A Division League Title in the 09/10 season. This gave the club lots of hope for becoming a key contender of the local leagues.\n\n== Honours ==\n'''HVL A Division Cup'''\n\n* Winners 09/10\n\n\n'''HVL A Division'''\n\n* Winners 09/10\n\n\n'''HVL Premier & Dore Shield'''\n\n* Winners 16/17<br />\n\n'''Dore Shield'''\n\n* Runners-up 17/18<br />\n\n'''Roden Cup'''\n\n* Winners 09/10 Runners-Up 18/19<br />\n\n'''Central Midlands Football League Division One Cup'''\n\n* Winners 18/19\n\n== Reserves ==\nThe Reserves side currently compete in the Hope Valley A Division and are managed by Club Secretary, Nick Rosling. The Reserves comprise of a densely saturated squad with a vast age variety, and also play at Bakewell Recreation Ground.\n\n== Rivalries ==\n[[Bakewell]]<ref name=\":0\" />'s location in the heart of the [[Peak District]] pits them against plenty of local team's, the most fierce rivalry for the club is Youlgrave United FC.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n__FORCETOC__\n__INDEX__\n\n{{uncategorised|date=March 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Bakewell Town F.C.\n| image = [[File:Bakewell Town FC Crest.png|thumb|Bakewell Town FC Crest]]\n| fullname = Bakewell Town Football Club\n| founded = 1883\n| ground = Bakewell Recreation Ground\n| manager = Ross Davies\n| website = https://www.pitchero.com/clubs/bakewelltownfc/\n| pattern_b1 = _lightbluestripes\n| shorts1 = 33CEFF\n| socks1 = 33CEFF\n}}'''Bakewell Town Football Club''' is a [[Association football|football]] club based in [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derbyshire|title=Derbyshire|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2020}}, England. They are current members of the [[Central Midlands Football League]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centralmidlandsleague.pitchero.com/|title=Central Midlands Football League|website=centralmidlandsleague.pitchero.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Division One South\n\n== History ==\nThe club were pitched at the inaugural meeting held at the [[Midland Hotel, Derby|Midland Hotel]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hallmarkhotels.co.uk/hotels/hallmark-hotel-derby-midland/|title=Midland Hotel|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in [[Derby]] in 1883 as Bakewell FC in which an Association of [[Derbyshire]]<ref name=\":0\" /> Football Clubs was formed & called the [[Derbyshire County Football Association|Derbyshire Football Association]].\n\nThe first known proof of organised football being played in the town shows photos which date back to circa 1890's.\n\nBakewell Town had been hovering in all three of the [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope Valley]] Divisions in the 80s-90's as an influx of interest for football in the Town after [[England national football team|England]]\u2019s near miss in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]] resulted in plenty of playing resource as three teams Bakewell FC, Bakewell Wheatsheaf FC 1st & Bakewell Town Reserves met at the Manners Public House Hotel to broker a merger at the end of the 99/00 season, this saw two teams, a First Team and Reserve side playing under the banner of Bakewell Town FC formed with one Team residing in the top [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope Valley]] Premier Division and the other in the third tier B Division, this structure is still in order to this day.\n\nAfter several years hovering between the Premier and A Division of the HVL structure the 1st Team had a huge bout of success as they first secured the A Division Cup and followed that a year later winning the A Division League Title in the 09/10 season. This gave the club lots of hope for becoming a key contender of the local leagues.\n\n== Honours ==\n'''Hope Valley League Premier & Dore Shield'''\n\n* Winners 16/17<br />\n\n'''Dore Shield'''\n\n* Runners-up 17/18<br />\n\n'''Roden Cup'''\n\n* Runners-Up 18/19<br />\n\n'''Central Midlands Football League Division One Cup'''\n\n* Winners 18/19<br />\n\n== Rivalries ==\n[[Bakewell]]<ref name=\":0\" />'s location in the heart of the [[Peak District]] pits them against plenty of local team's, the most fierce rivalries for the club include Youlgrave United FC & Rowsley 86 FC.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n__FORCETOC__\n__INDEX__\n\n{{uncategorised|date=March 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Alfiefairest", "label": "safe", "comment": "honours section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bakewell_Town_FC"}
{"title_page": "French cruiser Tage", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- warships except submarines -->\n|infobox caption= <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n|display title= <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup -->\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Class before={{ship|French cruiser|Sfax||2}}\n|Class after={{ship|French cruiser|Amiral C\u00e9cille||2}}\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|France|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Tage''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length=\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Tage''''' was a [[protected cruiser]] built for the [[French Navy]] in the 1880s, the second vessel of that type built for the French fleet.\n\n==Design==\n''Tage'' was {{cvt|118.87|m|0}} [[long overall]], with a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{cvt|16.3|m|ftin}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{cvt|7.67|m|ftin}}. She [[displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{cvt|7469|LT|t|lk=on}}. Her [[hull (watercraft)|hull]] featured a pronounced [[naval ram|ram bow]] and short [[forecastle|fore]] and [[sterncastle]]s. As was typical for French warships of the period, she had a pronounced [[tumblehome]] shape and an overhanging [[stern]]. Her [[superstructure]] was minimal, consisting primarily of a small [[conning tower]] forward. Her crew consisted of 538&nbsp;officers and enlisted men.{{sfn|Gardiner|p=308}}\n\n''Tage'' was propelled by a pair of horizontal [[triple-expansion steam engine]]s, each driving a [[screw propeller]]. Steam was provided by twelve coal-burning [[fire-tube boiler]]s that were ducted into [[funnel (ship)|funnels]] located [[amidships]]. The power plant was rated to produce {{convert|12500|ihp|lk=on}} for a top speed of {{convert|19.2|kn|lk=in}}. Coal storage amounted to {{cvt|915|LT|t}} normally and up to {{cvt|1500|LT|t}} at full load. To supplement the steam engines on long voyages, she was originally fitted with a [[barque]] sailing rig with three [[mast (sailing)|masts]].{{sfn|Gardiner|p=308}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n  | editor1-last = Gardiner\n  | editor1-first = Robert\n  | year = 1979\n  | title = Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1860\u20131905\n  | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-85177-133-5\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Gardiner}}\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/conwaysallworlds0000unse_l2e2\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ropp|authorlink=Theodore Ropp\n  | first = Theodore\n  | title = The Development of a Modern Navy: French Naval Policy, 1871\u20131904\n  | editor-last = Roberts\n  | editor-first = Stephen S.\n  | year = 1987\n  | location = Annapolis\n  | publisher = Naval Institute Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-87021-141-6\n  |ref={{sfnRef|Ropp}}\n  }}\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- warships except submarines -->\n|infobox caption= <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n|display title= <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup -->\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Class before={{ship|French cruiser|Sfax||2}}\n|Class after={{ship|French cruiser|Amiral C\u00e9cille||2}}\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|France|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Tage''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length=\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Tage''''' was a [[protected cruiser]] built for the [[French Navy]] in the 1880s, the second vessel of that type built for the French fleet.\n\n==Design==\n''Tage'' was {{cvt|118.87|m|ftin}} [[long overall]], with a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{cvt|16.3|m|ftin}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{cvt|7.67|m|ftin}}. She [[displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{cvt|7469|LT|t|lk=on}}. Her [[hull (watercraft)|hull]] featured a pronounced [[naval ram|ram bow]] and short [[forecastle|fore]] and [[sterncastle]]s. As was typical for French warships of the period, she had a pronounced [[tumblehome]] shape and an overhanging [[stern]]. Her [[superstructure]] was minimal, consisting primarily of a small [[conning tower]] forward. Her crew consisted of 538&nbsp;officers and enlisted men.{{sfn|Gardiner|p=308}}\n\n''Tage'' was propelled by a pair of horizontal [[triple-expansion steam engine]]s, each driving a [[screw propeller]]. Steam was provided by twelve coal-burning [[fire-tube boiler]]s that were ducted into [[funnel (ship)|funnels]] located [[amidships]]. The power plant was rated to produce {{convert|12500|ihp|lk=on}} for a top speed of {{convert|19.2|kn|lk=in}}. Coal storage amounted to {{cvt|915|LT|t}} normally and up to {{cvt|1500|LT|t}} at full load. To supplement the steam engines on long voyages, she was originally fitted with a [[barque]] sailing rig with three [[mast (sailing)|masts]].{{sfn|Gardiner|p=308}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n  | editor1-last = Gardiner\n  | editor1-first = Robert\n  | year = 1979\n  | title = Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1860\u20131905\n  | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-85177-133-5\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Gardiner}}\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/conwaysallworlds0000unse_l2e2\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ropp|authorlink=Theodore Ropp\n  | first = Theodore\n  | title = The Development of a Modern Navy: French Naval Policy, 1871\u20131904\n  | editor-last = Roberts\n  | editor-first = Stephen S.\n  | year = 1987\n  | location = Annapolis\n  | publisher = Naval Institute Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-87021-141-6\n  |ref={{sfnRef|Ropp}}\n  }}\n", "name_user": "Parsecboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDesign", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_cruiser_Tage"}
