uary 2015 |publisher=Federation of American Scientists |location=Washington, DC |url=https://fas.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/2015-FAS-UK-NNPP-HEU-final2.pdf |access-date=12 September 2017 |ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wade |first=Troy E. II |editor-last=Mackby |editor-first=Jenifer |editor-last2=Cornish |editor-first2=Paul |title=US-UK Nuclear Cooperation After 50 Years |contribution=Nuclear Testing: A US Perspective |pp=200\u2013211 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Center for Strategic and International Studies Press |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-89206-530-1 |oclc=845346116 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wynn |first=Humphrey |year=1997 |title=RAF Strategic Nuclear Deterrent Forces, Their Origins, Roles and Deployment, 1946\u20131969. A documentary history |publisher=The Stationery Office |location=London |isbn=0-11-772833-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last = Young  |first = Ken |author-link=Ken Young |title=A Most Special Relationship: The Origins of Anglo-American Nuclear Strike Planning |journal=Journal of Cold War Studies |date=Spring 2007 |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=5\u201331 |doi=10.1162/jcws.2007.9.2.5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book  |last = Young  |first = Ken  |title = The American Bomb in Britain: US Air Forces' Strategic Presence 1946\u201364 |date = 2016  |location = Manchester  |publisher = Manchester University Press |isbn = 978-0-7190-8675-5 |oclc=942707047 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nti.org/media/pdfs/56_4.pdf Full text of the Agreement]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160308142716/http://www.acronym.org.uk/dd/dd77/77mda.htm Negotiations for extension to treaty] (2004)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080118030158/http://www.awe.co.uk/main_site/about_awe/history/timeline/1958/ US-UK Agreement], [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041217064919/http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/MDAlegal.htm Mutual Defence Agreement and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty \u2013 Legal Opinion]\n\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom|Nuclear technology}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1958 US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement}}\n[[Category:1958 in military history]]\n[[Category:1958 in the United Kingdom|Mutual Defence Agreement]]\n[[Category:1958 in the United States|Mutual Defence Agreement]]\n[[Category:Cold War treaties]]\n[[Category:Nuclear history of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons program of the United States]]\n[[Category:Treaties concluded in 1958]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom\u2013United States treaties]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom\u2013United States military relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|Nuclear weapons security pact}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2019}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name                    = US\u2013UK Mutual Defence Agreement \n| long_name               = Agreement between the Government of the United States of America and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland for Cooperation on the uses of Atomic Energy for Mutual Defense Purposes  \n| image                   = File:Defense.gov photo essay 080709-D-7203C-003.jpg\n| image_size              = <!-- 200px -->\n| alt                     = The logo contains the flags of the two countries overlaid with a stylised gold \"50\"\n| caption                 = Logo for celebrations commemorating the 50th anniversary of the treaty in 2008\n| type                    =\n| context                 =\n| date_drafted            =\n| date_signed             = {{Start date|1958|07|03|df=yes}}\n| location_signed         = Washington, DC\n| date_sealed             =\n| date_effective          = {{Start date|1958|08|04|df=yes}}\n| condition_effective     =\n| date_expiration         = {{End date|2024|12|31|df=yes}}\n| date_expiry             =\n| provisional_application =\n| mediators               = <!-- format this as a bullet list -->\n| negotiators             = <!-- format this as a bullet list -->\n| original_signatories    = <!-- format this as a bullet list -->\n| signatories             = [[John Foster Dulles]] (US)<br />[[Samuel Hood, 6th Viscount Hood]] (UK)\n| parties                 = <!-- format this as a bullet list -->\n| ratifiers               = <!-- format this as a bullet list -->\n| depositor               = <!-- OR: -->\n| depositories            = <!-- format this as a bullet list -->\n| citations               = <!-- format as XX [[Article on Treaty Series|TS]] YYY -->\n| language                = <!-- OR: -->\n| languages               = <!-- format this as a bullet list -->\n| wikisource              = <!-- OR: -->\n| wikisource1             = <!-- Up to 5 wikisourceN variables may be specified -->\n| wikisource2             =\n| wikisource3             =\n| wikisource4             =\n| wikisource5             =\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n\nThe 1958 '''US\u2013UK Mutual Defense Agreement''', or '''UK\u2013US Mutual Defence Agreement''', is a [[bilateral treaty]] between the United States and the United Kingdom on [[nuclear weapon]]s co-operation. The treaty's full name is '''Agreement between the Government of the United States of America and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland for Cooperation on the uses of Atomic Energy for Mutual Defense Purposes'''. It allows the United States and the UK to exchange nuclear materials, technology and information. While the US has [[nuclear sharing|nuclear co-operation]] agreements with other countries, including France and other [[NATO]] countries, this agreement is by far the most comprehensive. Because of the agreement's strategic value to Britain, [[Harold Macmillan]] (the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] who presided over the United Kingdom's entry into the agreement) called it \"the Great Prize\".{{sfn|Macmillan|1971|p=323}}\n\nThe treaty was signed on 3 July 1958, after the [[Soviet Union]] [[Sputnik crisis|shocked the American public]] with the launch of [[Sputnik]] on 4 October 1957, and the [[British hydrogen bomb programme]] successfully tested a [[thermonuclear device]] in the [[Operation Grapple]] test on 8 November. The Anglo-American [[Special Relationship]] proved mutually beneficial, although it was never one of equals; the United States was (and is) far larger than Britain both militarily and economically. Britain soon became dependent on the United States for its nuclear weapons, as it lacked the resources to produce a range of designs. The treaty allowed American nuclear weapons to be supplied to Britain through [[Project E]], for use by the [[Royal Air Force]] and [[British Army of the Rhine]].\n\nThe treaty provided for the sale to the UK of one complete [[nuclear marine propulsion|nuclear submarine propulsion]] plant, plus ten years' supply of [[enriched uranium]] to fuel it. Other nuclear material was also acquired from the United States under the treaty. Some 5.4 tonnes of UK-produced [[plutonium]] was sent to the US in return for {{convert|6.7|kg|lb}} of [[tritium]] and 7.5 tonnes of [[highly enriched uranium]] (HEU) between 1960 and 1979, although much of the HEU was used not for weapons, but as fuel for the growing fleet of UK [[nuclear submarine]]s. The treaty paved the way for the [[Polaris Sales Agreement]], and the [[Royal Navy]] ultimately acquired entire weapons systems, with the [[UK Polaris programme]] and [[Trident nuclear programme]] using American missiles with British nuclear warheads.\n\nThe treaty has been amended and renewed nine times. The most recent renewal extended it to 31 December 2024.\n\n== Background ==\n=== Quebec Agreement ===\n[[File:Winston Churchill at the Quebec Conference, August 1943 H32144.jpg|thumb|right|[[Quebec Conference, 1943|Quebec Conference]] in 1943. Seated are (left to right): [[Anthony Eden]], President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], the [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone|Countess of Athlone]] and [[Winston Churchill]]. Standing are (left to right): [[Alexander Cambridge, 1st Earl of Athlone|Earl of Athlone]] ([[Governor General of Canada]]), [[Mackenzie King]] ([[Prime Minister of Canada]]), Sir [[Alexander Cadogan]], and [[Brendan Bracken]].]]\nDuring the early part of the [[Second World War]], Britain had a [[nuclear weapons]] project, codenamed [[Tube Alloys]].{{sfn|Gowing|1964|pp=108\u2013111}} At the [[Quadrant Conference]] in August 1943, the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], [[Winston Churchill]], and the [[President of the United States]], [[Franklin Roosevelt]], signed the [[Quebec Agreement]], which merged Tube Alloys with the American [[Manhattan Project]] to create a combined British, American and Canadian project.{{sfn|Hewlett|Anderson|1962|p=277}} The Quebec Agreement established the [[Combined Policy Committee]] and the [[Combined Development Trust]] to co-ordinate their efforts.{{sfn|Hewlett|Anderson|1962|pp=285\u2013286}} Many of Britain's top scientists [[British contribution to the Manhattan Project|participated in the Manhattan Project]].{{sfn|Gowing|1964|pp=236\u2013242}}\n\nThe September 1944 [[Hyde Park Aide-M\u00e9moire]] extended both commercial and military co-operation into the post-war period,{{sfn|Gowing|1964|pp=340\u2013342}} but Roosevelt died on 12 April 1945, and it was not binding on subsequent administrations.{{sfn|Paul|2000|pp=72\u201373}} In fact, it was physically lost. When [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] Sir [[Henry Maitland Wilson]] raised the matter in a Combined Policy Committee meeting in June 1945, the American copy could not be found.{{sfn|Hewlett|Anderson|1962|pp=457\u2013458}} The Quebec Agreement specified that nuclear weapons would not be used against another country without mutual consent. On 4 July, Wilson gave British agreement for the [[atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|use of nuclear weapons against Japan]].{{sfn|Gowing|1964|p=372}} On 8 August the Prime Minister, [[Clement Attlee]], sent a message to President [[Harry Truman]] in which he referred to themselves as \"heads of the Governments which have control of this great force\".{{sfn|Goldberg|1964|p=410}}{{sfn|Hewlett|Anderson|1962|pp=372\u2013373}}\n\n=== Truman administration ===\nThe British government had trusted that the United States would continue to share nuclear technology, which it considered to be a joint discovery.{{sfn|Goldberg|1964|p=410}} On 9 November 1945, Attlee and the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], [[Mackenzie King]], went to Washington, DC, to confer with Truman about future co-operation in nuclear weapons and nuclear power.{{sfn|Gott|1963|p=240}}{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=73\u201377}} A Memorandum of Intention they signed on 16 November 1945 made Canada a full partner, and replaced the Quebec Agreement's requirement for \"mutual consent\" before using nuclear weapons with one for \"prior consultation\". There was to be \"full and effective co-operation in the field of atomic energy\", but British hopes were soon disappointed;{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|p=92}} this was only \"in the field of basic scientific research\".{{sfn|Paul|2000|pp=80\u201383}}{{sfn|Hewlett|Anderson|1962|p=468}}\n\nTechnical co-operation was ended by the [[United States Atomic Energy Act of 1946]] (McMahon Act), which forbade passing \"restricted data\" to the United States' allies under pain of death.{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=106\u2013108}} This partly resulted from the arrest for espionage of British physicist [[Alan Nunn May]] in February 1946, while the legislation was being debated.{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=105\u2013108}} Fearing a resurgence of [[United States non-interventionism|American isolationism]], and Britain losing its [[great power]] status, the British government restarted its own development effort,{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=181\u2013184}} now codenamed [[High Explosive Research]].{{sfn|Cathcart|1995|pp=23\u201324, 48, 57}}\n\nBy the end of 1947, {{convert|1900|lt}} of uranium ore from the [[Belgian Congo]] was stockpiled for the Combined Development Trust at [[Springfields]], near [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] in [[Lancashire]], as part of a wartime sharing agreement, along with {{convert|1350|lt}} for British use. To gain access to the stockpile for their own nuclear weapons project, the Americans opened negotiations that resulted in the ''[[Modus Vivendi]]'',{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=358\u2013360}} an agreement which was signed on 7 January 1948. This officially terminated all previous agreements, including the Quebec Agreement. It removed the British right of consultation on the use of nuclear weapons,{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=34\u201335}} allowed for limited sharing of technical information between the United States, Britain and Canada,{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=245\u2013254}}{{sfn|Hewlett|Duncan|1969|pp=281\u2013283}} and continued the Combined Policy Committee and the Combined Development Trust,{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=34\u201335}} although the latter was renamed the [[Combined Development Agency]].{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=352\u2013353}}{{sfn|Hewlett|Duncan|1969|p=285}}\n\nIn 1949, the Americans offered to make atomic bombs in the United States available for Britain to use if the British agreed to curtail their atomic bomb programme.{{sfn|Hewlett|Duncan|1969|pp=307\u2013308}} This would have given Britain nuclear weapons much sooner than its own target date of late 1952.{{sfn|Hewlett|Duncan|1969|p=310}} Only those bomb components required by war plans would be stored in the UK, the rest would be kept in the US and Canada.{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974a|pp=281\u2013283}} The offer was rejected by the British on the grounds that it was not \"compatible with our status as a first-class power to depend on others for weapons of this supreme importance\".{{sfn|Baylis|1995|p=75}}\n\nAs a counter-offer, the British proposed limiting the British programme in return for American bombs.{{sfn|Hewlett|Duncan|1969|pp=309\u2013310}} The opposition of key American officials, including [[Lewis Strauss]] from the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission]] (AEC), and Senators [[Bourke B. Hickenlooper]] and [[Arthur Vandenberg]] of the [[Joint Committee on Atomic Energy]] (JCAE), coupled with security concerns aroused by the 2 February 1950 arrest of the British physicist [[Klaus Fuchs]], as an [[atomic spy]], caused the proposal to be dropped.{{sfn|Hewlett|Duncan|1969|pp=312\u2013314}} The June 1951 defection of [[Donald Maclean (spy)|Donald Maclean]], who had served as a British member of the Combined Policy Committee from January 1947 to August 1948, reinforced the Americans' distrust of British security arrangements.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=74\u201375}}\n\n=== Eisenhower administration ===\nThe first British atomic bomb was successfully tested in [[Western Australia]] in [[Operation Hurricane]] on 3 October 1952,{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974b|pp=493\u2013495}}\nbut although it was more advanced than the American bombs of 1946, Britain was still several years behind in nuclear weapons technology.{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974b|pp=474\u2013475}} On 1 November, the United States conducted [[Ivy Mike]], the first [[nuclear test]] of a true [[thermonuclear weapon|thermonuclear device]] (also known as a hydrogen bomb).{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|pp=16\u201320}} The JCAE saw little benefit for the United States from sharing technology with Britain.{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|pp=27\u201330}}{{sfn|Gowing|Arnold|1974b|pp=498\u2013500}} The [[Soviet Union]] responded to Ivy Mike with the test of [[Joe 4]], a [[boosted fission weapon]] on 12 August 1953.{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|pp=27\u201330}} This prompted President [[Dwight Eisenhower]], who was [[United States presidential inauguration|inaugurated]] in January 1953, to inform the [[United States Congress]] that the McMahon Act, which he considered a \"terrible piece of legislation\" and \"one of the most deplorable incidents in American history of which he personally felt ashamed\", was obsolete.{{sfn|Baylis|2008|pp=429\u2013430}}\n\n[[File:International Diplomacy.jpg|thumb|left|President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] (second from right) and Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]] (left foreground) meet for talks in Bermuda in March 1957 to repair the rift created by the 1956 [[Suez Crisis]].]]\nAt the three-power Bermuda Conference in December 1953, Eisenhower and Churchill,{{sfn|Paul|2000|pp=200\u2013201}} who had become prime minister again on 25 October 1951,{{sfn|Farmelo|2013|pp=372\u2013375}} discussed the possibility of the United States giving Britain access to American nuclear weapons in wartime.{{sfn|Paul|2000|pp=200\u2013201}} This came to be called [[Project E]].{{sfn|Baylis|2008|pp=429\u2013430}} There were technical and legal issues that had to be overcome before American bombs could be carried in British aircraft. The United States would have to disclose their weights and dimensions, while their delivery would require data concerning their ballistics. Further down the track, there would also be issues of custody, security and targeting. The release of such information was restricted by the McMahon Act.{{sfn|Young|2016|pp=200\u2013201}}\n\nThis was amended on 30 August 1954 by the [[Atomic Energy Act of 1954]], which allowed for greater exchange of information with foreign nations,{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=140\u2013141}} paving the way for the Agreement for Co-operation Regarding Atomic Information for Mutual Defence Purposes, which was signed on 15 June 1955.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=147\u2013149}} On 13 June 1956, another agreement was concluded, for the transfer of [[nuclear marine propulsion|nuclear submarine propulsion]] technology to Britain, saving the British government millions of pounds in research and development costs. This precipitated a row with the JCAE over whether this was permitted under the Atomic Energy Act of 1954, and whether Britain met the security standards set by the 1955 agreement. With the [[1956 United States presidential election|1956 presidential election]] approaching, Eisenhower was forced to rescind the offer.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=161\u2013164}}\n\nThe October 1956 [[Suez Crisis]] brought relations between Britain and the United States to a low ebb.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=171\u2013174}} When Eisenhower met with the new Prime Minister, [[Harold Macmillan]], in Bermuda in March 1957, he raised the possibility of basing US [[intermediate range ballistic missile]] (IRBM) systems in the UK.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=174\u2013177}} This came to be called [[Project Emily]].{{sfn|Young|2016|pp=98\u201399}} There were also discussions on exchanging nuclear submarine propulsion technology for information on the British [[Calder Hall]] [[nuclear power plant]], allowing the [[United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority]] (UKAEA) to purchase uranium ore from Canada, and co-ordinating the war plans of [[RAF Bomber Command]] with those of the [[Strategic Air Command]].{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=180\u2013181}}\n\nAlthough the IRBM negotiations pre-dated the Suez Crisis, it suited the British government to tout the IRBM deal as a demonstration that the rift had been healed.{{sfn|Young|2007|p=8}} The [[British hydrogen bomb programme]] attempted to detonate a [[thermonuclear device]] in the [[Operation Grapple]] test series at [[Kiritimati|Christmas Island]] in the Pacific.{{sfn|Baylis|1994|pp=166\u2013170}} The test series was facilitated by the United States, which also claimed the island.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=159\u2013160}} Although the first tests were unsuccessful,{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|p=147}} the Grapple X test on 8 November achieved the desired result.{{sfn|Baylis|1994|pp=166\u2013170}}{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|pp=160\u2013162}}\n==Negotiation==\n===Sputnik crisis===\n[[File:HD.3C.001 (13406014683).jpg|thumb|right|Eisenhower (left) lays the cornerstone for the new [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] (AEC) building in [[Germantown, Maryland]], on 8 November 1957. [[United States Congress Joint Committee on Atomic Energy|Joint Committee on Atomic Energy]] (JCAE) Chairman [[Carl T. Durham]] (centre) and AEC Chairman [[Lewis Strauss]] (right) look on.]]\nThe successful development of British thermonuclear weapons came at an opportune time to renew negotiations with the United States. The Soviet Union's launch of [[Sputnik 1]], the world's first [[artificial satellite]], on 4 October 1957, came as a tremendous shock to the American public, who had trusted that American technological superiority ensured their invulnerability. Now, suddenly, there was incontrovertible proof that, in some areas at least, the Soviet Union was actually ahead. In the widespread calls for action in response to the [[Sputnik crisis]], officials in the United States and Britain seized an opportunity to mend their relationship.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=199\u2013201}} At the suggestion of [[Harold Caccia, Baron Caccia|Harold Caccia]], the [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to the United States|British Ambassador to the United States]], Macmillan wrote to Eisenhower on 10 October urging that the two countries pool their resources,{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|p=199}} as Macmillan put it, to meet the Soviet challenge on every front, \"military, economic and political\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1955-57v27/d306 |access-date=12 September 2017 |title=Foreign Relations of the United States, 1955\u20131957, Western Europe and Canada, Volume XXVII \u2013 Document 306  |publisher=Office of the Historian, United States Department of State }}</ref>\n\nMacmillan flew to Washington, DC, for talks on 25 October.{{sfn|Divine|1993|p=34}} He had concerns that the disastrous 10 October [[Windscale fire]] might prove a stumbling block in negotiations,{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=438}} as it might reflect badly on British expertise and provide ammunition for opponents of closer co-operation with the UK. He ordered extra copies of the report into the fire to be destroyed, and for the printers to destroy their [[Letterpress printing|type]].<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |title=Britain Suppressed Details of '57 Atomic Disaster: Macmillan feared the loss of U.S. cooperation |first=Steve |last=Lohr |date=2 January 1988 |p=3 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/02/world/britain-suppressed-details-of-57-atomic-disaster.html |access-date=18 August 2019 }}</ref> He immediately sensed how shaken the Americans had been by Sputnik.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=199\u2013201}} It placed the Eisenhower administration under great public pressure to act on the deployment of IRBMs by a shocked and distraught nation.{{sfn|Divine|1993|pp=73\u201374}}\n\nEisenhower and Macmillan agreed to form a study group headed by Sir Richard Powell, the Permanent Secretary to the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], and [[Donald A. Quarles]], the [[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense]], to consider how the deployment of IRBMs to Britain might be expedited.{{sfn|Divine|1993|p=34}} Another study group, under Strauss and Sir [[Edwin Plowden, Baron Plowden|Edwin Plowden]], the head of the UKAEA, would investigate nuclear co-operation and the exchange of nuclear information.{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=438}} The personal relationship developed between Plowden and Strauss would be crucial in converting the latter over to the idea of providing information to Britain.{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=440}}\n\nBy December, most of the issues with the IRBM negotiations had been ironed out,{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=442}} and a formal agreement was drawn up on 17 December, although it was not until the end of the month that it was definitely determined that Britain would receive [[PGM-17 Thor|Thor]] and not [[PGM-19|Jupiter]] missiles.{{sfn|Wynn|1997|p=287}} However, the nuclear submarine propulsion effort was running into trouble. Under the July 1956 agreement and a February 1957 directive from Eisenhower, [[Royal Navy]] officers had been assigned to study the US Navy's nuclear submarine programme. By October 1957, its head, [[Rear Admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Hyman G. Rickover]], felt that their questions were slowing the deployment of the [[UGM-27 Polaris|Polaris]] submarine-launched IRBM at a critical time. He feared that any delay might cause Congress to favour land-based missiles. By December, the British liaison officers were complaining of slow response to their questions. Rickover proposed that [[Westinghouse Electric Company|Westinghouse]] be permitted to sell the Royal Navy a nuclear submarine reactor, which would allow it to immediately proceed with building its own nuclear-powered submarine. The British government endorsed this idea, as it would save it a great deal of money.{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=203}}{{sfn|Baylis|2008|pp=441\u2013442}}\n\n===Amending the McMahon Act===\nFor their part, the British wanted the McMahon Act's restrictions on nuclear co-operation to be relaxed. They wanted to know the weight and dimensions, fusing and firing sequences, safety features, and in-flight procedures; the information that would allow American bombs to be carried in British [[V-bombers]], and American warheads to be fitted to British [[Blue Streak (missile)|Blue Streak]] missiles.{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=203}} This would potentially save millions of pounds and avoid domestic political complications if Britain had to persist with nuclear testing during an international moratorium.{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=440}} While the British knew what they wanted, there was no consensus among the Americans as to what they wanted to provide.{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=203}} The [[United States Secretary of State]], [[John Foster Dulles]], was concerned that a special relationship with Britain might complicate the United States' relationships with its other allies.{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=439}} Strauss in particular felt that a proposal to give hydrogen bomb secrets to the British would likely not get past the JCAE, and counselled drafting amendments that were sufficiently vague as to give the president the authority he needed without arousing its ire.{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=203}} Eisenhower declared that the US and UK were \"interdependent\", and pledged to ask Congress to amend the McMahon Act.{{sfn|Moore|2010|p=33}}\n\nCrucially, he managed to secure the support of [[Carl T. Durham]], the chairman of the JCAE. Eisenhower met with congressional leaders on 3 December 1957, and pressed for more discretion to co-operate with all America's [[NATO]] allies, and not just Britain.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=207\u2013208}} Indeed the administration negotiated agreements with Australia, Canada and NATO.{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=214}} While Eisenhower did not yet have wholehearted support for the proposal, outright opposition from [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Clinton P. Anderson]] failed to attract much support.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=207\u2013208}} On 27 January 1958, Strauss sent Durham the administration's proposed legislative changes,{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=214}} and the JCAE Subcommittee on Agreements for Cooperation, chaired by Senator [[John O. Pastore]], held hearings from 29 to 31 January. Quarles and [[Major General (United States)|Major General]] [[Herbert Loper]], the Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Atomic Energy Affairs, were forced to deal with pointed questions about [[nuclear proliferation]].{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=215\u2013219}} British information security, or the lack thereof, no longer seemed so important now that the Soviet Union was apparently ahead, and the United Kingdom had independently developed the hydrogen bomb,{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=224\u2013225}} but the JCAE objected to the terms of the proposed deal to trade British uranium-235 for American [[plutonium]], under which the US would pay [[United States dollar|USD]] $30 per gram for plutonium that cost USD $12 per gram to produce in the UK.{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=224}}\n\nThe amendments were passed by the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] on 19 June, but not without changes. It now limited exchanges of nuclear weapons data to nations that had made substantial progress in the field. The same restriction applied to the actual transfer of non-nuclear components of nuclear weapons. American nuclear weapons were to remain under US custody and could only be turned over to allies in the event of war. The sale of nuclear reactors for submarines and nuclear fuel for them and other military reactors was permitted. Only Britain qualified as a nation that had made substantial progress.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=232\u2013233}} The bill passed Congress on 30 June 1958, and was signed into law by Eisenhower on 2 July 1958.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=234\u2013236}} The 1958 US\u2013UK Mutual Defence Agreement was signed by Dulles and [[Samuel Hood, 6th Viscount Hood|Samuel Hood]], the British Minister in Washington, DC, on 3 July,<ref name=\"full text\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nti.org/media/pdfs/56_4.pdf |title=Agreement between the Government of the United States of America and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland for Cooperation on the uses of Atomic Energy for Mutual Defence Purposes |publisher=Nuclear Threat Initiative |access-date=1 June 2017 }}</ref> and approved by Congress on 30 July.{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=238}}\n\n==Implementation==\n===Details of the agreement===\n[[File:Defense.gov photo essay 080709-D-7203C-008.jpg|thumb|left|UK Defence Minister [[Des Browne]] (right) addresses a reception hosted by US Defense Secretary [[Robert M. Gates]] (left) commemorating the 50th anniversary of the US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement in Washington, DC, on 9 July 2008.]]\nThe agreement enables the US and the UK to exchange [[classified information]] with the objective of improving each party's \"atomic weapon design, development, and fabrication capability\".<ref name=\"full text\"/> While the US has nuclear co-operation agreements with other countries, including France and some NATO countries, none are similar in scope to the US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2014-11-17/214429/ |title=Military Alliances: Written question \u2013 214429 |first=Tobias |last=Ellwood |author-link=Tobias Ellwood |publisher=UK Parliament |work=Hansard |date=24 November 2014 |access-date=25 November 2014}}</ref> Macmillan called it \"the Great Prize\".{{sfn|Macmillan|1971|p=323}}\n\nArticle 2 of the treaty covered joint development of defence plans; the mutual training of personnel in the use and defence against nuclear weapons; the sharing of intelligence and evaluation of enemy capabilities; the development of nuclear delivery systems; and the research, development and design of military reactors.{{sfn|Mills|2014|p=3}} The treaty called for the exchange of \"classified information concerning atomic weapons when, after consultation with the other Party, the communicating Party determines that the communication of such information is necessary to improve the recipient's atomic weapon design, development and fabrication capability\".<ref name=\"full text\"/> The US would communicate information about atomic weapons that were similar to British atomic weapons. For the immediate future, that would exclude information about thermonuclear weapons.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=236\u2013237}}  Confidential intelligence matters are also covered by the agreement. The UK government has not published these sections \"because of the necessity for great confidentiality and because of the use that such information would be to other would-be nuclear states.  In other words, it might well assist proliferation\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Lord Bach |author-link=Willy Bach, Baron Bach |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200304/ldhansrd/vo040622/text/40622-03.htm#st_27|title=UK-US Mutual Defence Agreement|work=Hansard |publisher=UK Parliament |date=22 June 2004 |access-date=15 March 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312132029/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200304/ldhansrd/vo040622/text/40622-03.htm| archive-date= 12 March 2007 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nArticle 3 provided for the sale to the UK of one complete nuclear submarine propulsion plant, plus the uranium needed to fuel it for ten years.{{sfn|Mills|2014|p=3}} Due to concerns expressed by the JCAE, the AEC would determine the price that Britain would pay for [[highly enriched uranium]] (HEU).{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=236\u2013237}} The treaty did not allow for non-nuclear components of nuclear weapons to be given to Britain. It was amended on 7 May 1959 to give Britain access to non-nuclear components,{{sfn|Botti|1987|p=238}} and to permit the transfer of special nuclear material such as [[plutonium]], HEU and [[tritium]].{{sfn|Moore|2010|pp=84\u201385}} The treaty paved the way for the subsequent [[Polaris Sales Agreement]],{{sfn|Baylis|2008|pp=455\u2013456}} which was signed on 6 April 1963.{{sfn|Jones|2017|p=444}} The two agreements have been \"the cornerstone of the UK-US nuclear relationship for nearly 60 years\".{{sfn|Mills|2014|p=3}}\n\n===Nuclear weapons development===\nThe AEC invited the British government to send representatives to a series of meetings in Washington, DC, on 27 and 28 August 1958 to work out the details. The US delegation included [[Willard Libby]], AEC deputy chairman; Loper; [[Brigadier General (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Alfred Starbird]], AEC Director of Military Applications; [[Norris Bradbury]], director of the [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]]; [[Edward Teller]], director of the [[Lawrence Livermore Laboratory]]; and [[James W. McRae]], president of the [[Sandia Corporation]]. The British representatives were Sir [[Frederick Brundrett]], the [[Chief Scientific Adviser to the Ministry of Defence]], and Victor Macklen from the Ministry of Defence; and [[William Penney]], [[William Richard Joseph Cook|William Cook]] and E. F. Newly from the [[Atomic Weapons Research Establishment]] at [[Aldermaston]]. The Americans disclosed the details of nine of their nuclear weapon designs: the [[Mark 7 nuclear bomb|Mark 7]], [[Mark 15 nuclear bomb|Mark 15]]/[[Mark 39 nuclear bomb|39]], [[W19 (nuclear artillery shell)|Mark 19]], [[W25 (nuclear warhead)|Mark 25]], [[Mark 27 nuclear bomb|Mark 27]], [[B28 nuclear bomb|Mark 28]], [[W31|Mark 31]], [[W33 (nuclear warhead)|Mark 33]] and [[W34 (nuclear warhead)|Mark 34]]. In return, the British provided the details of seven of theirs, including [[Yellow Sun (nuclear weapon)#Green Grass|Green Grass]]; Pennant, the boosted device which had been detonated in the Grapple Z test on 22 August; Flagpole, the two-stage device scheduled for 2 September; Burgee, scheduled for 23 September; and the three-stage Halliard 3. The Americans were impressed with the British designs, particularly with Halliard 1, the heavier version of Halliard 3. Cook therefore changed the Grapple Z programme to fire Halliard 1 instead of Halliard 3.{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|pp=202\u2013205}} Macmillan noted in his diary, with satisfaction that:{{quote|in some respects we are as far, and even further, advanced in the art than our American friends. They thought interchange of information would be all ''give''. They are keen that we should complete our series, especially the last megaton, the character of which is novel and of deep interest to them.{{sfn|Macmillan|1971|p=565}} }}\n\nAn early benefit of the agreement was to allow the UK to \"Anglicise\" the [[W28]] nuclear warhead as the [[Red Snow]] warhead for the [[Blue Steel missile]].{{sfn|Moore|2010|pp=88\u201389}} The British designers were impressed by the W28, which was not only lighter than the British Green Grass warhead used in [[Yellow Sun (nuclear weapon)|Yellow Sun]], but remarkably more economical in its use of expensive fissile material. The Yellow Sun Mark 2 using Red Snow cost [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]500,000 compared with \u00a31,200,000 for the Mark 1 with Green Grass.{{sfn|Moore|2010|pp=104\u2013105}} A 1974 CIA proliferation assessment noted that: \"In many cases [Britain's sensitive technology in nuclear and missile fields] is based on technology received from the US and could not legitimately be passed on without US permission.\"<ref name=SNIE-4-1-74>{{cite report|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB240/snie.pdf|series=Special National Intelligence Estimate|title=Prospects for Further Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons|page=40|publisher=CIA|date=23 August 1974|id=SNIE 4-1-74|accessdate=20 January 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213130511/http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB240/snie.pdf| archivedate=13 February 2008 | url-status=live}}</ref> The UK [[National Audit Office (United Kingdom)|National Audit Office]] noted that most of the [[UK Trident programme]] warhead development and production expenditure was incurred in the US, which supplied special materials and \"certain warhead-related components and services\".<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.danplesch.net/articles/WMD/WMDMar10FINAL.pdf|title=The Future of Britain's WMD|page=15|first=Dan |last=Plesch |publisher=Foreign Policy Centre |date=March 2006 |access-date=15 March 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621034126/http://www.danplesch.net/articles/WMD/WMDMar10FINAL.pdf |archive-date = 21 June 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfn|Downey|1987|pp=3, 10, 18}} There is evidence that the warhead design of the [[British Trident system]] is similar to, or even based upon, the US [[W76]] warhead fitted in US Navy [[Trident missile]]s, with design and blast model data supplied to the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fas.org/blog/ssp/2006/12/britains_next_nuclear_era_1.php|title=Britain's Next Nuclear Era|publisher=[[Federation of American Scientists]]|date=7 December 2006|accessdate=15 March 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206035127/http://www.fas.org/blog/ssp/2006/12/britains_next_nuclear_era_1.php |archivedate=6 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fas.org/blog/ssp/images/W76req.pdf|title=Stockpile Stewardship Plan: Second Annual Update (FY 1999)|publisher=[[United States Department of Energy]] |accessdate=15 March 2007|date=April 1998 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325150817/http://www.fas.org/blog/ssp/images/W76req.pdf |archive-date=25 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nBritain soon became dependent on the United States for its nuclear weapons, as it lacked the resources to produce a range of designs.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=238\u2013241}} The treaty allowed the UK to receive US nuclear weapons for the Royal Air Force (RAF) and [[British Army of the Rhine]] (BAOR) under Project E.{{sfn|Moore|2010|pp=114\u2013115}} Similar custody arrangements were made for the Thor missiles supplied under Project Emily.{{sfn|Moore|2010|pp=98\u201399}} The UK was able to carry out underground nuclear tests at the US [[Nevada Test Site]], where the first British test took place on 1 March 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awe.co.uk/main_site/about_awe/history/timeline/1962/|title=UK Mounts First Underground Nuclear Test (UGT)|publisher=[[Atomic Weapons Establishment]]|accessdate=15 March 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118030522/http://www.awe.co.uk/main_site/about_awe/history/timeline/1962/ |archivedate=18 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[British nuclear testing in the United States]] continued until abruptly halted by President [[George H. W. Bush]] in October 1992.{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=462}}{{sfn|Wade|2008|p=209}} Major subcritical nuclear tests continued to occur, most notably the Etna test in February 2002, and the Krakatau test in February 2006.{{sfn|Wade|2008|p=210}}\n\n===Special nuclear materials barter===\n[[File:HMS Splendid S106.jpeg|thumb|right|The Royal Navy's {{sclass-|Swiftsure|submarine|1}} {{HMS|Splendid|S106|6}}]]\nUnder the agreement 5.37 tonnes of UK-produced plutonium was sent to the US in exchange for 6.7&nbsp;kg of tritium and 7.5 tonnes of HEU between 1960 and 1979. A further 470&nbsp;kg of plutonium was swapped between the US and the UK for reasons that remain classified.<ref name=mod-plutonium-account>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061213032416/http://www.mod.uk/NR/rdonlyres/B31B4EF0-A584-4CC6-9B14-B5E89E6848F8/0/plutoniumandaldermaston.pdf |archivedate=13 December 2006 |url=http://www.mod.uk/NR/rdonlyres/B31B4EF0-A584-4CC6-9B14-B5E89E6848F8/0/plutoniumandaldermaston.pdf |title=Plutonium and Aldermaston \u2013 an historical account |publisher=[[UK Ministry of Defence]] |date=4 September 2001 |accessdate=15 March 2007 }}</ref> Some of the UK-produced plutonium was used in 1962 by the US for the only known nuclear weapon test of [[reactor-grade plutonium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://permanent.access.gpo.gov/websites/osti.gov/www.osti.gov/html/osti/opennet/document/press/pc29.html|title=Additional Information Concerning Underground Nuclear Weapon Test of Reactor-Grade Plutonium|publisher=[[US Department of Energy]] |accessdate=15 March 2007 |date=June 1994}}</ref> The plutonium sent to the US included some produced in UK civil [[Magnox]] reactors, and the US gave assurances that this civil plutonium was not used in the US nuclear weapons programme. It was used in civil programmes which included [[californium]] production and reactor research.<ref name=mod-plutonium-account />\n\nSome of the [[fissile material]]s for the UK Trident warhead were purchased from the US,{{sfn|Downey|1987|pp=3, 10, 18}}  but much of the HEU supplied by the US was used not for weapons, but as fuel for the growing fleet of UK [[nuclear submarine]]s. Under the treaty, the US supplied the UK with not just nuclear submarine propulsion technology, but a complete [[S5W]] [[pressurised water reactor]] of the kind used to power the US {{sclass-|Skipjack|submarine|0}} submarines. This was used in the Royal Navy's first nuclear-powered submarine, {{HMS|Dreadnought|S101|6}}, which was [[ceremonial ship launching|launched]] in 1960 and [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] in 1963. The S5W was fuelled by uranium enriched to between 93 and 97 per cent [[uranium-235]].{{sfn|Ritchie|2015|p=3}} Reactor technology was transferred from Westinghouse to [[Rolls-Royce Limited|Rolls Royce]],{{sfn|Moore|2010|p=35}} which used it as the basis for its [[PWR1]] reactor used in the UK's  {{sclass-|Valiant|submarine|5}}, {{sclass-|Resolution|submarine|5}}, {{sclass-|Churchill|submarine|5}}, {{sclass-|Swiftsure|submarine|5}} and {{sclass-|Trafalgar|submarine|5}} submarines.{{sfn|Ritchie|2015|p=4}}\n\nThe UK produced HEU at its facility in [[Capenhurst]], but production for military purposes ceased there in March 1963.{{sfn|Moore|2010|pp=197\u2013199}} Thereafter, uranium oxide was imported from Australia, Canada, Namibia, South Africa, the United States and Zaire, and processed into [[uranium hexafluoride]] at Springfields. It was then shipped to the US, where it was enriched at the [[Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant]] near [[Piketon, Ohio]]. HEU was then flown back to the UK in RAF aircraft.{{sfn|Ritchie|2015|p=3}} In 1994, with the Portsmouth plant about to close, the treaty was amended, with the US requirement to \"provide\" uranium enrichment services changed to one to \"arrange\" them.<ref name=\"full text\" /> By March 2002, the UK had a stockpile of 21.86 tonnes of HEU, about 80 years' supply for the Royal Navy's nuclear-powered submarines.{{sfn|Ritchie|2015|p=7}}\n\n===Joint Working Groups===\nMost of the activity under the treaty is information exchange through Joint Working Groups (JOWOG). At least 15 of these were established in 1959.{{sfn|Moore|2010|p=90}} Subjects investigated included:{{quote|one-point safety, computer codes, metallurgy and fabrication technology for beryllium, uranium and plutonium, corrosion of uranium in the presence of water and water vapour, underground effects tests, outer-space testing, clandestine testing, the technology of lithium compounds, high explosives, deuterium monitors, extinguishing plutonium fires, high-speed cameras, mechanical safing, liquid and solid explosive shock initiation, environmental sensing switches, neutron sources, tritium reservoirs, telemetry, hydrodynamic and shock relations for problems with spherical and cylindrical symmetry, [[nuclear cross section]]s, radiochemistry, atomic demolition munitions, warhead hardening, asymmetric detonations, terrorist nuclear threat response, nuclear weapons accidents and waste management.{{sfn|Moore|2010|p=90}} }}\n\nBetween 2007 and 2009, staff of the [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]] paid 2,000 visits to US nuclear facilities.{{sfn|Mills|2014|p=5}} {{As of|2014}} there are also two enhanced collaborations jointly developing capabilities:\n* Enhanced Nuclear Safety \u2013 to develop architectures and technologies related to warhead safety; and\n* Warhead Electrical System \u2013 to develop architectures and technologies for warhead electrical systems.<ref name=parliament-wq209762>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2014-09-26/209762/ |title=Written question 209762: Angus Robertson 26-09-2014 |first=Philip |last=Dunne |publisher=UK Parliament |date=21 October 2014 |access-date=27 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mutual benefit===\nThe Anglo-American [[Special Relationship]] proved mutually beneficial, although it was never one of equals; the United States was far larger than Britain both militarily and economically.{{sfn|Botti|1987|pp=238\u2013241}} [[Lorna Arnold]] noted that:{{quote|The balance of advantage in the exchanges was necessarily in Britain's favour but they were not entirely one-sided. In some areas, notably electronics and high explosives, the British were equal or perhaps even superior, and in many areas they had valuable ideas to contribute, as the American scientists, and notably Teller, appreciated.{{sfn|Arnold|Pyne|2001|p=215}} }}\nA 1985 report by the State Department's [[Bureau of Intelligence and Research]] reported that the US was \"profoundly involved and benefited greatly\" from the treaty.{{sfn|Baylis|2008|p=461}}\n\n==Renewal==\n[[File:Lisa E. Gordon-Hagerty and Stephen Lovegrove.jpg|thumb|left|[[National Nuclear Security Administration|NNSA]] Administrator [[Lisa Gordon-Hagerty]] and [[Stephen Lovegrove]] cut the ribbon on the US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement 60th Anniversary commemorative exhibit in June 2018]]\nThe treaty was amended on 7 May 1959, 27 September 1968, 16 October 1969, 22 June 1974, 5 December 1979, 5 June 1984, 23 May 1994 and 14 June 2004. Most amendments merely extended the treaty for another five or ten years; others added definitions and made minor changes.<ref name=\"full text\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/24227.pdf |title=Treaties in Force |publisher=[[United States Department of State]] |access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acronym.org.uk/old/archive/docs/0406/doc14.htm |title=Disarmament Documentation: Amendment to the 1958 US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement (on nuclear weapons' cooperation), June 2004 |publisher=Acronym Institute |access-date=12 September 2016 }}</ref> {{As of|2020}}, the most recent renewal was on 22 July 2014, extending the treaty to 31 December 2024, with minor changes for the [[Trident nuclear programme]].<ref name=\"2014 amendment\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cs-ukus-amendment-to-the-agreement-for-cooperation-on-the-uses-of-atomic-energy-for-mutual-defense-purposes |title=UK/US: Amendment to the Agreement for Cooperation on the Uses of Atomic Energy for Mutual Defense Purposes |publisher=[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] |accessdate=22 March 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6XE8cp0N5?url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cs-ukus-amendment-to-the-agreement-for-cooperation-on-the-uses-of-atomic-energy-for-mutual-defense-purposes |archivedate=22 March 2015 |date=16 October 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/defence-and-security-blog/2014/jul/29/nuclear-weapons-us-uk-cooperation |title=UK-US sign secret new deal on nuclear weapons |newspaper=The Guardian |date=30 July 2014 |first=Richard |last=Norton-Taylor |access-date=8 September 2017 }}</ref>\n\nA 2004 legal opinion obtained by the [[British American Security Information Council]] (BASIC) argued that renewal of the treaty violated Article VI of the [[Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty]], which required signatories to take steps towards nuclear disarmament. This was not accepted by the British government. In July 2014 [[Baroness Warsi]], the Senior [[Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]] from 2012 to 2014,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/oct/11/sayeeda-warsi-why-i-quitgovernment-has-lost-moral-compass-middle-east-gaza|title=Lady Warsi on Palestine, Islam, quitting ... and how to stay true to your beliefs|first=Mark |last=Townsend|work=The Guardian|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref> stated that the government's position was that:{{quote|We are committed to the goal of a world without nuclear weapons and firmly believe that the best way to achieve this is through gradual disarmament negotiated through a step-by-step approach within the framework of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty. The UK has a strong record on nuclear disarmament and continues to be at the forefront of international efforts to control proliferation, and to make progress towards multilateral nuclear disarmament. The UK-USA Mutual Defence Agreement is, and will continue to be, in full compliance with our obligations under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.{{sfn|Mills|2014|p=10}} }}\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book |last=Arnold |first=Lorna | authorlink=Lorna Arnold |last2=Pyne |first2=Katherine  |author-link2=Kate Pyne  |title=Britain and the H-bomb |location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire ; New York |publisher=Palgrave |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-230-59977-2 |oclc=753874620 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Baylis |first=John  |title=The Development of Britain's Thermonuclear Capability 1954\u201361: Myth or Reality? |journal=Contemporary Record |issn=1361-9462 |volume=8 |issue=1 |date=Summer 1994 |pp=159\u2013164 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Baylis |first=John |year=1995 |title=Ambiguity and Deterrence: British Nuclear Strategy 1945\u20131964 |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press |isbn=0-19-828012-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Baylis |first=John |date=June 2008 |title=The 1958 Anglo-American Mutual Defence Agreement: The Search for Nuclear Interdependence |journal=The Journal of Strategic Studies |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=425\u2013466 |issn=0140-2390 |doi= 10.1080/01402390802024726|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Botti |first=Timothy J. |title=The Long Wait: the Forging of the Anglo-American Nuclear Alliance, 1945\u201358 |location=New York |publisher=Greenwood Press |year=1987 |series=Contributions in Military Studies |isbn=978-0-313-25902-9 |oclc=464084495 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cathcart |first=Brian |author-link=Brian Cathcart |title=Test of Greatness: Britain's Struggle for the Atom Bomb |publisher=John Murray |year=1995 |isbn=0-7195-5225-7|location=London |oclc=31241690 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Divine |first=Robert A. |title=The Sputnik Challenge |url=https://archive.org/details/sputnikchallenge0000divi |url-access=registration |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-19-505008-0 |oclc=875485384 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Downey |first=Gordon |author-link=Gordon Downey |title=Ministry of Defence and Property Services Agency: Control and Management of the Trident Programme |publisher=Her Majesty's Stationary Office |location=-London |date=29 June 1987 |oclc=655304084 |isbn=978-0-10-202788-4 |url=https://www.nao.org.uk/pubsarchive/wp-content/uploads/sites/14/2018/11/Ministry-of-Defence-and-Property-Services-Agency-Control-and-Management-of-the-Trident-Programme.pdf |access-date=12 December 2019  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Farmelo |first=Graham |author-link=Graham Farmelo |title=Churchill's Bomb: How the United States Overtook Britain in the First Nuclear Arms Race |publisher=Basic Books |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-465-02195-6 |oclc=858935268 |location=New York |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/churchillsbombho0000farm }}\n* {{cite journal | last=Goldberg |first=Alfred | jstor=2610825 | title=The Atomic Origins of the British Nuclear Deterrent | journal=International Affairs |date=July 1964 | volume=40 | issue=3 | pages=409\u2013429 | doi=10.2307/2610825 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal | last=Gott |first=Richard | title=The Evolution of the Independent British Deterrent | journal=International Affairs |issn=0020-5850 |date=April 1963 | volume=39 | issue=2 | pages=238\u2013252 | doi=10.2307/2611300 | jstor=2611300 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Gowing |first=Margaret |authorlink=Margaret Gowing |title=Britain and Atomic Energy 1939\u20131945  |publisher=Macmillan |year=1964 |location=London |oclc=3195209 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last = Gowing |first = Margaret   | first2 = Lorna | last2 = Arnold | authorlink2=Lorna Arnold | year = 1974a | title=Independence and Deterrence: Britain and Atomic Energy, 1945\u20131952, Volume 1, Policy Making | publisher= Macmillan| location = London | isbn = 0-333-15781-8| oclc = 611555258 | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last = Gowing |first = Margaret  | first2 = Lorna | last2 = Arnold  | year=1974b  |title=Independence and Deterrence: Britain and Atomic Energy, 1945\u20131952, Volume 2, Policy and Execution  |location= London |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=0-333-16695-7|oclc= 946341039 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hewlett |first=Richard G. |authorlink=Richard G. Hewlett |last2=Anderson |first2=Oscar E. |url=https://www.governmentattic.org/5docs/TheNewWorld1939-1946.pdf |title=The New World, 1939\u20131946 |publisher=Pennsylvania State University Press |year=1962 |isbn=0-520-07186-7|location=University Park |oclc=637004643 |ref=harv |accessdate=26 March 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Hewlett |first=Richard G.  |last2=Duncan |first2=Francis |title=Atomic Shield, 1947\u20131952 |series=A History of the United States Atomic Energy Commission |url=http://energy.gov/sites/prod/files/2013/04/f0/Hewlett%20and%20Duncan%20-%20Atomic%20Shield%20%28complete%29.pdf |accessdate=7 March 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania State University Press |location=University Park, Pennsylvania |year=1969 |isbn=0-520-07187-5|oclc=3717478 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Jones |first=Matthew |author-link=Matthew Jones (historian) |series=The Official History of the UK Strategic Nuclear Deterrent |title=Volume I: From the V-Bomber Era to the Arrival of Polaris, 1945\u20131964 |location=Abingdon, Oxfordshire |publisher=Routledge |year=2017 |isbn=978-1-138-67493-6 |oclc=957683181|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Macmillan |first=Harold |author-link=Harold Macmillan |title=Riding the Storm: 1956\u20131959 |url=https://archive.org/details/ridingstorm195611956macm |url-access=registration |location=London |publisher=Macmillan |year=1971 |isbn=978-0-333-10310-4 |oclc=198741 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite report |last=Mills |first=Claire |title=UK-US Mutual Defence Agreement |date=17 September 2014 |publisher=House of Commons Library |url=https://www.nuclearinfo.org/sites/default/files/House%20of%20Commons%20Standard%20Note%20US-UK%20Mutual%20Defence%20Agreement%20Sept%202014.pdf |access-date=12 September 2017 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last=Moore|first=Richard|title=Nuclear Illusion, Nuclear Reality: Britain, the United States, and Nuclear Weapons, 1958\u201364|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|series=Nuclear Weapons and International Security since 1945|location=Basingstoke, Hampshire|year=2010|isbn=978-0-230-21775-1|oclc=705646392|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Paul |first=Septimus H. |year=2000 |title=Nuclear Rivals: Anglo-American Atomic Relations, 1941\u20131952 |location=Columbus, Ohio |publisher=Ohio State University Press |isbn= 978-0-8142-0852-6|oclc=43615254 |ref = harv }}\n* {{cite report |last=Ritchie |first=Nick  |title=The UK Naval Nuclear Propulsion Programme and Highly Enriched Uranium |date=February 2015 |publisher=Federation of American Scientists |location=Washington, DC |url=https://fas.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/2015-FAS-UK-NNPP-HEU-final2.pdf |access-date=12 September 2017 |ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wade |first=Troy E. II |editor-last=Mackby |editor-first=Jenifer |editor-last2=Cornish |editor-first2=Paul |title=US-UK Nuclear Cooperation After 50 Years |contribution=Nuclear Testing: A US Perspective |pp=200\u2013211 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Center for Strategic and International Studies Press |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-89206-530-1 |oclc=845346116 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wynn |first=Humphrey |year=1997 |title=RAF Strategic Nuclear Deterrent Forces, Their Origins, Roles and Deployment, 1946\u20131969. A documentary history |publisher=The Stationery Office |location=London |isbn=0-11-772833-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last = Young  |first = Ken |author-link=Ken Young |title=A Most Special Relationship: The Origins of Anglo-American Nuclear Strike Planning |journal=Journal of Cold War Studies |date=Spring 2007 |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=5\u201331 |doi=10.1162/jcws.2007.9.2.5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book  |last = Young  |first = Ken  |title = The American Bomb in Britain: US Air Forces' Strategic Presence 1946\u201364 |date = 2016  |location = Manchester  |publisher = Manchester University Press |isbn = 978-0-7190-8675-5 |oclc=942707047 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nti.org/media/pdfs/56_4.pdf Full text of the Agreement]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160308142716/http://www.acronym.org.uk/dd/dd77/77mda.htm Negotiations for extension to treaty] (2004)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080118030158/http://www.awe.co.uk/main_site/about_awe/history/timeline/1958/ US-UK Agreement], [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041217064919/http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/MDAlegal.htm Mutual Defence Agreement and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty \u2013 Legal Opinion]\n\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom|Nuclear technology}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1958 US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement}}\n[[Category:1958 in military history]]\n[[Category:1958 in the United Kingdom|Mutual Defence Agreement]]\n[[Category:1958 in the United States|Mutual Defence Agreement]]\n[[Category:Cold War treaties]]\n[[Category:Nuclear history of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons program of the United States]]\n[[Category:Treaties concluded in 1958]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom\u2013United States treaties]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom\u2013United States military relations]]\n", "name_user": "185.44.129.186", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1958_US%E2%80%93UK_Mutual_Defence_Agreement"}
{"title_page": "M\u00f6ller Ice Stream", "text_new": "[[Image:FRicestreams.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[Radarsat]] image of ice streams, including the M\u00f6ller, flowing into the [[Filchner-Ronne Ice Shelf]]]]\n'''M\u00f6ller Ice Stream''' ({{Coord|82|20|S|63|30|W|source:GNIS|display=inline,title}}) is an Antarctic [[ice stream]] that drains an area of {{Convert|66000|sqkm}} of the [[West Antarctic Ice Sheet]] as it flows north-northeast into the [[Ronne Ice S]] to the west of [[Foundation Ice Stream]]. The drainage basin of this ice stream is separated by the [[Rambo Nunataks]] from the drainage basin of Foundation Ice Stream.<ref name=USGSgnismoller/><ref name=bingham2009/>\n\nThe feature was delineated from U.S. [[Landsat]] imagery commissioned by the [[Institut f\u00fcr Angewandte Geod\u00e4sie]], [[Frankfurt am Main]], Germany, recorded January\u2013March, 1986. It was named after German engineer Professor [[Dietrich M\u00f6ller (surveyor)|Dietrich M\u00f6ller]], Director of the Institute for Land Survey at the [[Technical University of Braunschweig]] from 1972, and Deputy Leader and in charge of geodetic work at [[Filchner Station]] on the Ronne Ice Shelf in 1979\u201380.<ref name=USGSgnismoller/>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of glaciers in the Antarctic]]\n* [[List of Antarctic ice streams]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=USGSgnismoller>{{cite gnis | type = antarid | id = 10136| name = M\u00f6ller Ice Stream | accessdate = 2013-10-31}}</ref>\n<ref name=bingham2009>{{cite journal |author=Bingham R.G., Seigert M.J. |title=Quantifying subglacial bed roughness in Antarctica: implications for ice-sheet dynamics and history |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |volume=28 |pages=223\u2013236 |year=2009 |doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2008.10.014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{usgs-gazetteer|id=10136| name = M\u00f6ller Ice Stream}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moller Ice Stream}}\n\n[[Category:Ice streams of Queen Elizabeth Land]]\n[[Category:Filchner-Ronne Ice Shelf]]\n\n\n{{QueenElizabethLand-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[Image:FRicestreams.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[Radarsat]] image of ice streams, including the M\u00f6ller, flowing into the [[Filchner-Ronne Ice Shelf]]]]\n'''M\u00f6ller Ice Stream''' ({{Coord|82|20|S|63|30|W|source:GNIS|display=inline,title}}) is an Antarctic [[ice stream]] that drains an area of {{Convert|66000|sqkm}} of the [[West Antarctic Ice Sheet]] as it flows north-northeast into the [[Ronne Ice Shelf]] to the west of [[Foundation Ice Stream]]. The drainage basin of this ice stream is separated by the [[Rambo Nunataks]] from the drainage basin of Foundation Ice Stream.<ref name=USGSgnismoller/><ref name=bingham2009/>\n\nThe feature was delineated from U.S. [[Landsat]] imagery commissioned by the [[Institut f\u00fcr Angewandte Geod\u00e4sie]], [[Frankfurt am Main]], Germany, recorded January\u2013March, 1986. It was named after German engineer Professor [[Dietrich M\u00f6ller (surveyor)|Dietrich M\u00f6ller]], Director of the Institute for Land Survey at the [[Technical University of Braunschweig]] from 1972, and Deputy Leader and in charge of geodetic work at [[Filchner Station]] on the Ronne Ice Shelf in 1979\u201380.<ref name=USGSgnismoller/>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of glaciers in the Antarctic]]\n* [[List of Antarctic ice streams]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=USGSgnismoller>{{cite gnis | type = antarid | id = 10136| name = M\u00f6ller Ice Stream | accessdate = 2013-10-31}}</ref>\n<ref name=bingham2009>{{cite journal |author=Bingham R.G., Seigert M.J. |title=Quantifying subglacial bed roughness in Antarctica: implications for ice-sheet dynamics and history |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |volume=28 |pages=223\u2013236 |year=2009 |doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2008.10.014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{usgs-gazetteer|id=10136| name = M\u00f6ller Ice Stream}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moller Ice Stream}}\n\n[[Category:Ice streams of Queen Elizabeth Land]]\n[[Category:Filchner-Ronne Ice Shelf]]\n\n\n{{QueenElizabethLand-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "185.200.102.237", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6ller_Ice_Stream"}
{"title_page": "Trapeta Mayson", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n|name         = Trapeta B. Mayson\n|image        = \n|image_size   = \n|caption      = \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = 1967\n|birth_place  = [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]]\n|occupation   = Poet, educator, social worker, non-profit administrator\n|genre        = Poetry\n|notableworks = ''She was once herself'', ''Mocha memories'', ''By the roadside'' \n}}\n\n'''Trapeta B. Mayson''' (1967- ) is a Liberian-born poet, teacher, social worker, and non-profit administrator residing in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], USA. Her writing primarily centers on the experiences of  immigrants to the United States, the struggles of people dealing with conflict in [[Liberia]], and the daily lives of average people, especially women and girls.<ref name=\":0\" /> She received a Masters in Social Work from [[Bryn Mawr College]] and an MBA from [[Villanova University]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She was selected as the fifth [[Poet Laureate of Philadelphia]] in 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/arts/philadelphia-poet-laureate-trapeta-mayson-20191212.html|title=Trapeta B. Mayson named next poet laureate of Philadelphia|last=Harden|first=Brandon T.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early life==\n\nBorn in [[Monrovia]], Liberia, Mayson immigrated to the United States in 1975 with her family at the age of eight and settled in Philadelphia.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://moonstoneartscenter.org/moonstone-arts-center-events/tuesday-march-27-7pm-%e2%80%93-poetry/|title=The Moonstone Poetry Series Presents Trapeta Mason & Quincy Scott Jones \u2013 Moonstone Arts Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/historic-germantown/|title=Historic Germantown welcomes Liberia native Trapeta Mayson as its new executive director|website=WHYY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> She grew up in the [[North Philadelphia]] and [[Germantown, Philadelphia|Germantown]] neighborhoods. According to Mayson, she considers herself to be a \"sum of two continents... two countries, two sets of powerful people: my birth country of Liberia, and my beloved Philadelphia.\u201d<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/nonprofit-leader-by-day-artist-by-night-meet-phillys-new-poet-laureate-trapeta-b-mayson/|title=Nonprofit leader by day, artist by night: Meet Philly\u2019s new poet laureate Trapeta B. Mayson|website=WHYY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nShe received her undergraduate degree in political science from [[Temple University]] in 1993.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chestnuthilllocal.com/2013/09/06/award-winning-poet-from-liberia-to-gtown-with-love/|title=Award-winning poet: From Liberia to G\u2019town, with love|last=Mancinelli|first=Lou|date=2013-09-06|website=Chestnut Hill Local Philadelphia PA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> Mayson is a licensed social worker and received her masters in social work from the Bryn Mawr College Graduate School of Social Work and Social Research in 1995.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brynmawr.edu/news/trapeta-b-mayson-mss-95-named-phillys-new-poet-laureate|title=Trapeta B. Mayson, M.S.S. '95, Named Philly's New Poet Laureate {{!}} Bryn Mawr College|website=www.brynmawr.edu|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> In addition, she holds an MBA from the Villanova University School of Business.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Career and writing==\n{{external media | width = 250px | align = left | video1 = [https://vimeo.com/218692596 \u201cOutbound Poetry Festival: Trapeta Mayson & Monnette Sudler (1/4)\"], April 15, 2017, , Part 1 of 4, Philadelphia Contemporary | video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kzQiZ18ZMcY \"A Poem by Trapeta B. Mayson - Experience\"], \"Father\", May 18, 2009, WHYY Education | video3 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A_P-dDAynlQ \u201cGCabaret 2008 - Trapeta Mayson and Vena Jefferson\"], November 11, 2008, Leewayfoundation}}\n\nIn the early 2000s Mason was the Vice President of Education and Family Learning at the [[Please Touch Museum]], a museum focusing on creating tactile learning experiences for younger children via \"purposeful play\" that also correlates to local and state educational standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyingkitemedia.com/features/pleasetouchmuseum0306.aspx|title=Please Touch Museum rises as thought leader for early childhood development|last=|first=|date=|website=www.flyingkitemedia.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2014 to 2018, Mayson served as the Executive Director for Historic Germantown, an historic preservation collective that manages and promotes 16 historic houses in the Germantown neighborhood of Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901193127/http://www.freedomsbackyard.com/about/|title=About {{!}} Historic Germantown|date=2015-09-01|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> During her tenure there, she worked with former Poet Laureate of Philadelphia [[Yolanda Wisher]] on various poetry events along with an initiative to bring artists into Historic Germantown with the goal of helping teens to engage with the historic properties and learn about Philadelphia and American history. The 2015 program, named Culture Keepers, partnered with the Parkway Northwest High School for Peace and Social Justice to pilot a program of historic site visits where students engaged in photography, captioning photos in [[Instagram]], [[geocaching]], and conducting [[oral history]] interviews with local elders. Later, local writers guided the high-schoolers in creating poems reflecting on their learned experiences, which the students presented live at a Historic Germantown open house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/centerforperformanceandcivicpractic/docs/cpcp_philadelphia_final|title=CPCP Catalyst Initiative: Philadelphia|last=Mayson|first=Trapeta|last2=Wisher|first2=Yolanda|date=2017-02-21|website=Issuu|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nSince 2019, concurrent with her poetry readings and outreach as Poet Laureate of Philadelphia, Mayson has worked as the program officer for a mental health service agency in the [[Kensington, Philadelphia|Kensington]] neighborhood of Philadelphia.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMayson is a member of the Green Street Artists Cooperative, a multicultural artistic community in Germantown.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aspenwords.org/programs/summer-words/6228-2/|title=EMERGING WRITER FELLOWSHIPS|website=Aspen Words|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.greenestreetartists.org/mem_Gallery.aspx|title=Members Gallery - Greene Street Artists Cooperative|last=|first=|date=2020-02-10|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Her written work has been exhibited at the [[Colored Girls Museum]] in Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecoloredgirlsmuseum.com/artists-page|title=Artists Page|website=The Colored Girls Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> Some of her poetic verses are part of a mural by artist [[Ife Nii Owoo]] at the Logan Branch of the [[Free Library of Philadelphia]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://libwww.freelibrary.org/blog/post/4003|title=Blog: A New Poet Laureate for Philadelphia...|website=Free Library of Philadelphia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nThe author has collaborated with jazz guitarist [[Monnette Sudler|Monette Sudler]] on the Sisters in Music project since 2000.<ref name=\":9\" /> They have multiple recordings, including two recent poetry and jazz pieces, \"Scat\" and \"How we got through\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://trapetamayson.com/|title=POET Performer Teaching artist Consultant|last=Mayson|first=Trapeta|website=Trapeta B. Mayson|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> In their spoken and sung word and music collaboration, Mayson extolls her female viewers to \"Keep climbing\" as \"You can only go up from here.\" and to \"Fly, girl, fly.\" despite their struggles against various oppressions, while Sudler encourages them to \"Step up to the plate.\" in a softball-themed metaphor for life.<ref>{{Citation|last=Contemporary|first=Philadelphia|title=Outbound Poetry Festival: Trapeta Mayson &amp; Monnette Sudler (1/4)|date=2017-05-23|url=https://vimeo.com/218692596|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nMayson taught at the Art Sanctuary for 8 years<ref name=\":6\" />, along with serving as an artist in residence at Art Sanctuary\u2019s after-school teen arts program, and [[Painted Bride Art Center]]\u2019s ArtLAB Youth Poetry Series.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer experience as an immigrant and a social worker has directly informed her writing, where she focuses on social issues such as immigration and mental illness, often with a perspective on gender and race, using a first-person, \u201ceveryday voice\u201d that sometimes utilizes Liberian English.<ref name=\":5\" /> Her second chapbook, ''She Was Once Herself'', tells the story of her mother's immigration from Liberia to the United States, her struggles and triumphs in adapting to a new country, the family's problems obtaining citizenship, and later her nervous breakdown with subsequent diagnosis of [[schizophrenia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sablelitmag.org/kadijasesay/blog/trapeta-mayson-march-14/|title=Trapeta Mayson March 14 \u2013 Kadija Sesay|last=|first=|date=|website=Kadija Sesay - Literary Activist|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nIn her poem \"We Are All Trees Here\", Mayson relates how immigrants to the United States feel as they are labeled as enemies in their new country and experience fear from being undocumented, using the metaphor of [[Sapotaceae|sapo]] trees for family members struggling for survival in forests that are threatened by [[clearcutting]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stitcher.com/s?eid=64767314|title=We Are the Enemies from Love Jawns: A Mixtape|website=www.stitcher.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> In \"Father\", the poet creates a vignette of a nattily-dressed older man who was laid-off from his workplace after many years, and must now work multiple low-wage jobs to support his family.<ref name=\":8\" /> In \"First Job Advice\", an older Liberian immigrant gives advice to her recently-arrived compatriot about how to serve as a cleaning woman for an upper-class family, so that the other woman can earn money and send for her children to come to the United States in order that they \"won't have to know the first jobs we do\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sablelitmag.org/trapeta-b-mayson/|title=Trapeta B. Mayson - First Job Advice (1972)|last=|first=|date=2014-01-14|website=Sable Lit Mag|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> \n\nMayson's tenure at Historic Germantown provided background for some of her poetry honoring African-American slaves, such as her poem \"Happy birthday Dinah\" about a slave named Dinah who resided at the [[Stenton (mansion)|Stenton Mansion]] in the [[Logan, Philadelphia|Logan]] section of Philadelphia, and was enslaved by family members of statesman and former mayor [[James Logan (statesman)|James Logan]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theartblog.org/2019/12/getting-to-know-phillys-new-poet-laureate/|title=Getting to know Philly's new Poet Laureate|date=2019-12-20|website=Artblog|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nHer experience in mental health care has prompted Mayson to seek out new partnerships that use writing to educate the public about mental heath issues, such as recognizing [[Mental Health Awareness Month]], or considering suicide rates and creating \"healing verse\" for communities.<ref name=\":6\" /> In past workshops, the author has fostered the creation of toolkits for healing that she calls \u201cRecipe For\", in which participants reveal the key issues impacting their lives, and facilitators assist them to create a list of writing \"ingredients\" that they can use  independently to promote self-healing.<ref name=\":6\" /> In addition, she has conducted poetry and writing workshops with LGBTQ communities, undocumented immigrants, incarcerated people, women survivors of domestic abuse, and sex workers, among other marginalized groups, in which her purpose is to provide a platform to empower people to speak who often do not have the opportunity to have their voices heard.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Works by Trapeta B. Mayson==\n'''Books of Poetry'''\n\n*2018: ''She was once herself.'', OCLC [https://www.worldcat.org/title/she-was-once-herself/oclc/889180469 1055273795]\n*2008: ''Mocha melodies''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://writing.upenn.edu/wh/calendar/0504.html|title=WH Calendar: May 2004|website=writing.upenn.edu|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n*2004: ''By the roadside : for Liberian survivors of war.,'' OCLC [https://www.worldcat.org/title/by-the-roadside-for-liberian-survivors-of-war/oclc/60326929 1055273795]\n\n'''Contributor to Periodicals and Anthologies'''\n\n*2008: ''Letter to my sister''., The American Poetry Review, v37 n4 (20080701): 28, {{ISBN|9781944211615|}} OCLC [https://www.worldcat.org/title/letter-to-my-sister/oclc/5542763498 1049785850]\n\nMayson has also published in periodicals such as ''[[Aesthetica]] Magazine,The [[The American Poetry Review|American Poetry Review]],'' ''Aura, a [[University of Alabama]] Literary Journal''; ''[[Cave Canem Foundation|Cave Canem]]\u2019s literary review'', ''Epiphany Literary Journal, Margie: The American Journal of Poetry and Strong Medicine: American Journal of Poetry''; among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennbookcenter.com/event/poetry-reading-w-ir%C3%A8ne-mathieu-trapeta-mayson-raquel-salas-rivera|title=Poetry Reading w/ Ir\u00e8ne Mathieu, Trapeta Mayson, & Raquel Salas Rivera {{!}} Penn Book Center|website=www.pennbookcenter.com|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\nMayson was chosen as the fifth poet laureate of Philadelphia in 2019, under the auspices of the Free Library of Philadelphia. According to the selection committee, the poet was chosen because of her ability to balance a full-time poetic writing practice with participation in many local Philadelphia organizations.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to the poet, in her role she aspires to \u201ctouch base with social service agencies, particularly those pertaining to mental health, in [Philly\u2019s] communities.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> She considers the role to be \u201c...like a poetry ambassador for the city, ... Engaging communities, young people, people from all over the city, and engaging them in the creation of poetry, appreciation of poetry.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kywnewsradio.radio.com/articles/news/philly-s-new-poetry-ambassador-champions-creativity|title=Philly\u2019s new \u2018poetry ambassador\u2019 champions creativity, engagement|date=2019-12-12|website=KYW|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she was awarded an Aspen Words Emerging Writers fellowship from the [[Aspen Institute]].<ref name=\":7\" /> She also served as a juror for the 2019 Scholastic National Writing Awards from the [[Alliance for Young Artists & Writers]] in the category of Poetry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artandwriting.org/who-we-are/jurors/2019-national-writing-jurors/|title=2019 National Writing Jurors \u2013 Scholastic Art & Writing Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nThe author was nominated for a [[Pushcart Prize]] in 2016.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nFrom the Leeway Foundation, she received both an Art and Change Grant in 2014 and a Transformation Award in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leeway.org/artists/trapeta_b_mayson/|title=Trapeta B. Mayson|website=Leeway Foundation|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nThe poet was a 2002 fellow of the [[Pew Center for Arts & Heritage|Pew Center for Arts and Heritage]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewcenterarts.org/people/trapeta-b-mayson|title=Trapeta B. Mayson|last=admin|date=2016-11-30|website=The Pew Center for Arts & Heritage|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\nShe was a fellow of the [[Pennsylvania Council on the Arts|Pennsylvania Council of the Arts]] in both 2000 and 2004.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also==\n{{Portal|Liberia|Africa|Biography|Literature|Poetry}}\n*[[List of Liberian writers]]\n*[[List of African writers by country]]\n*[[Liberian Americans]]\n*[[List of alumni of Villanova University|List of Villanova University Alumni]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes\n|lcheading=\n|viaf=2201360}}\n\n* {{Official website|https://trapetamayson.com//}}\n\n=== Selected Poems ===\n\n*''[http://www.sablelitmag.org/trapeta-b-mayson/ Brother]''\n*''[http://www.sablelitmag.org/trapeta-b-mayson/ First Job Advice]''\n*[http://iiammoon.blogspot.com/2011/04/poetic-licensetrapeta-b-mayson.html ''I Long to Be'' (From Mocha Melodies)]\n*[https://www.personalizedmedicinebydesign.com/story-cure/ Stories Cure]\n\n=== Interviews ===\n\n*[https://www.theartblog.org/2019/12/getting-to-know-phillys-new-poet-laureate/ Getting to know Philly\u2019s new Poet Laureate - Trapeta Mayson, December 20,2019, Artblog]\n\n=== Performances and recordings ===\n\n*[https://kywnewsradio.radio.com/media/audio-channel/poems-by-philly-s-new-poet-laureate-trapeta-b-mayson 3 Poems by Trapeta Mayson - KYW Newsradio]\n*[http://www.sablelitmag.org/kadijasesay/blog/trapeta-mayson-march-14/ Cecilia Too Soon]\n*[https://www.nypl.org/audiovideo/celebrating-little-magazine-contemporary-america-0 Trapeta Mayson - An Evening with Epiphany Magazine]\n*[https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/love-jawns-a-mixtape/e/64767314 ''We Are All Trees Here'' (Love Jawns: A Mixtape - We Are All Enemies)]\n\n=== Exhibitions ===\n\n* [https://www.ifestudio3.com/public-art?lightbox=dataItem-j52xvmgk Read: a Pathway to Hope] (mural arts collaboration with artist Ife Nii Owoo)\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayson, Trapeta}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Temple University alumni]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College alumni]]\n[[Category:Villanova University alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberian women]]\n[[Category:Liberian writers]]\n[[Category:American social workers]]\n[[Category:Poets Laureate of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Municipal Poets Laureate in the United States]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:American spoken word artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pew Fellows in the Arts]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Monrovia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n|name         = Trapeta B. Mayson\n|image        = \n|image_size   = \n|caption      = \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = 1967\n|birth_place  = [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]]\n|occupation   = Poet, educator, social worker, non-profit administrator\n|genre        = Poetry\n|notableworks = ''She was once herself'', ''Mocha memories'', ''By the roadside'' \n}}\n\n'''Trapeta B. Mayson''' (1967- ) is a Liberian-born poet, teacher, social worker, and non-profit administrator residing in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], USA. Her writing primarily centers on the experiences of  immigrants to the United States, the struggles of people dealing with conflict in [[Liberia]], and the daily lives of average people, especially women and girls.<ref name=\":0\" /> She received a Masters in Social Work from [[Bryn Mawr College]] and an MBA from [[Villanova University]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She was selected as the fifth [[Poet Laureate of Philadelphia]] in 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/arts/philadelphia-poet-laureate-trapeta-mayson-20191212.html|title=Trapeta B. Mayson named next poet laureate of Philadelphia|last=Harden|first=Brandon T.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early life==\n\nBorn in [[Monrovia]], Liberia, Mayson immigrated to the United States in 1975 with her family at the age of eight and settled in Philadelphia.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://moonstoneartscenter.org/moonstone-arts-center-events/tuesday-march-27-7pm-%e2%80%93-poetry/|title=The Moonstone Poetry Series Presents Trapeta Mason & Quincy Scott Jones \u2013 Moonstone Arts Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/historic-germantown/|title=Historic Germantown welcomes Liberia native Trapeta Mayson as its new executive director|website=WHYY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> She grew up in the [[North Philadelphia]] and [[Germantown, Philadelphia|Germantown]] neighborhoods. According to Mayson, she considers herself to be a \"sum of two continents... two countries, two sets of powerful people: my birth country of Liberia, and my beloved Philadelphia.\u201d<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/nonprofit-leader-by-day-artist-by-night-meet-phillys-new-poet-laureate-trapeta-b-mayson/|title=Nonprofit leader by day, artist by night: Meet Philly\u2019s new poet laureate Trapeta B. Mayson|website=WHYY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nShe received her undergraduate degree in political science from [[Temple University]] in 1993.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chestnuthilllocal.com/2013/09/06/award-winning-poet-from-liberia-to-gtown-with-love/|title=Award-winning poet: From Liberia to G\u2019town, with love|last=Mancinelli|first=Lou|date=2013-09-06|website=Chestnut Hill Local Philadelphia PA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> Mayson is a licensed social worker and received her masters in social work from the Bryn Mawr College Graduate School of Social Work and Social Research in 1995.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brynmawr.edu/news/trapeta-b-mayson-mss-95-named-phillys-new-poet-laureate|title=Trapeta B. Mayson, M.S.S. '95, Named Philly's New Poet Laureate {{!}} Bryn Mawr College|website=www.brynmawr.edu|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> In addition, she holds an MBA from the Villanova University School of Business.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Career and writing==\n{{external media | width = 250px | align = left | video1 = [https://vimeo.com/218692596 \u201cOutbound Poetry Festival: Trapeta Mayson & Monnette Sudler (1/4)\"], April 15, 2017, , Part 1 of 4, Philadelphia Contemporary | video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kzQiZ18ZMcY \"A Poem by Trapeta B. Mayson - Experience\"], \"Father\", May 18, 2009, WHYY Education | video3 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A_P-dDAynlQ \u201cGCabaret 2008 - Trapeta Mayson and Vena Jefferson\"], November 11, 2008, Leewayfoundation}}\n\nIn the early 2000's Mason was the Vice President of Education and Family Learning at the [[Please Touch Museum]], a museum focusing on creating tactile learning experiences for younger children via \"purposeful play\" that also correlates to local and state educational standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyingkitemedia.com/features/pleasetouchmuseum0306.aspx|title=Please Touch Museum rises as thought leader for early childhood development|last=|first=|date=|website=www.flyingkitemedia.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2014 to 2018, Mayson served as the Executive Director for Historic Germantown, an historic preservation collective that manages and promotes 16 historic houses in the Germantown neighborhood of Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901193127/http://www.freedomsbackyard.com/about/|title=About {{!}} Historic Germantown|date=2015-09-01|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> During her tenure there, she worked with former Poet Laureate of Philadelphia [[Yolanda Wisher]] on various poetry events along with an initiative to bring artists into Historic Germantown with the goal of helping teens to engage with the historic properties and learn about Philadelphia and American history. The 2015 program, named Culture Keepers, partnered with the Parkway Northwest High School for Peace and Social Justice to pilot a program of historic site visits where students engaged in photography, captioning photos in [[Instagram]], [[geocaching]], and conducting [[oral history]] interviews with local elders. Later, local writers guided the high-schoolers in creating poems reflecting on their learned experiences, which the students presented live at a Historic Germantown open house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/centerforperformanceandcivicpractic/docs/cpcp_philadelphia_final|title=CPCP Catalyst Initiative: Philadelphia|last=Mayson|first=Trapeta|last2=Wisher|first2=Yolanda|date=2017-02-21|website=Issuu|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nSince 2019, concurrent with her poetry readings and outreach as Poet Laureate of Philadelphia, Mayson has worked as the program officer for a mental health service agency in the [[Kensington, Philadelphia|Kensington]] neighborhood of Philadelphia.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMayson is a member of the Green Street Artists Cooperative, a multicultural artistic community in Germantown.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aspenwords.org/programs/summer-words/6228-2/|title=EMERGING WRITER FELLOWSHIPS|website=Aspen Words|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.greenestreetartists.org/mem_Gallery.aspx|title=Members Gallery - Greene Street Artists Cooperative|last=|first=|date=2020-02-10|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Her written work has been exhibited at the [[Colored Girls Museum]] in Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecoloredgirlsmuseum.com/artists-page|title=Artists Page|website=The Colored Girls Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> Some of her poetic verses are part of a mural by artist [[Ife Nii Owoo]] at the Logan Branch of the [[Free Library of Philadelphia]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://libwww.freelibrary.org/blog/post/4003|title=Blog: A New Poet Laureate for Philadelphia...|website=Free Library of Philadelphia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nThe author has collaborated with jazz guitarist [[Monnette Sudler|Monette Sudler]] on the Sisters in Music project since 2000.<ref name=\":9\" /> They have multiple recordings, including two recent poetry and jazz pieces, \"Scat\" and \"How we got through\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://trapetamayson.com/|title=POET Performer Teaching artist Consultant|last=Mayson|first=Trapeta|website=Trapeta B. Mayson|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> In their spoken and sung word and music collaboration, Mayson extolls her female viewers to \"Keep climbing\" as \"You can only go up from here.\" and to \"Fly, girl, fly.\" despite their struggles against various oppressions, while Sudler encourages them to \"Step up to the plate.\" in a softball-themed metaphor for life.<ref>{{Citation|last=Contemporary|first=Philadelphia|title=Outbound Poetry Festival: Trapeta Mayson &amp; Monnette Sudler (1/4)|date=2017-05-23|url=https://vimeo.com/218692596|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nMayson taught at the Art Sanctuary for 8 years<ref name=\":6\" />, along with serving as an artist in residence at Art Sanctuary\u2019s after-school teen arts program, and [[Painted Bride Art Center]]\u2019s ArtLAB Youth Poetry Series.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer experience as an immigrant and a social worker has directly informed her writing, where she focuses on social issues such as immigration and mental illness, often with a perspective on gender and race, using a first-person, \u201ceveryday voice\u201d that sometimes utilizes Liberian English.<ref name=\":5\" /> Her second chapbook, ''She Was Once Herself'', tells the story of her mother's immigration from Liberia to the United States, her struggles and triumphs in adapting to a new country, the family's problems obtaining citizenship, and later her nervous breakdown with subsequent diagnosis of [[schizophrenia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sablelitmag.org/kadijasesay/blog/trapeta-mayson-march-14/|title=Trapeta Mayson March 14 \u2013 Kadija Sesay|last=|first=|date=|website=Kadija Sesay - Literary Activist|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nIn her poem \"We Are All Trees Here\", Mayson relates how immigrants to the United States feel as they are labeled as enemies in their new country and experience fear from being undocumented, using the metaphor of [[Sapotaceae|sapo]] trees for family members struggling for survival in forests that are threatened by [[clearcutting]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stitcher.com/s?eid=64767314|title=We Are the Enemies from Love Jawns: A Mixtape|website=www.stitcher.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> In \"Father\", the poet creates a vignette of a nattily-dressed older man who was laid-off from his workplace after many years, and must now work multiple low-wage jobs to support his family.<ref name=\":8\" /> In \"First Job Advice\", an older Liberian immigrant gives advice to her recently-arrived compatriot about how to serve as a cleaning woman for an upper-class family, so that the other woman can earn money and send for her children to come to the United States in order that they \"won't have to know the first jobs we do\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sablelitmag.org/trapeta-b-mayson/|title=Trapeta B. Mayson - First Job Advice (1972)|last=|first=|date=2014-01-14|website=Sable Lit Mag|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> \n\nMayson's tenure at Historic Germantown provided background for some of her poetry honoring African-American slaves, such as her poem \"Happy birthday Dinah\" about a slave named Dinah who resided at the [[Stenton (mansion)|Stenton Mansion]] in the [[Logan, Philadelphia|Logan]] section of Philadelphia, and was enslaved by family members of statesman and former mayor [[James Logan (statesman)|James Logan]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theartblog.org/2019/12/getting-to-know-phillys-new-poet-laureate/|title=Getting to know Philly's new Poet Laureate|date=2019-12-20|website=Artblog|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nHer experience in mental health care has prompted Mayson to seek out new partnerships that use writing to educate the public about mental heath issues, such as recognizing [[Mental Health Awareness Month]], or considering suicide rates and creating \"healing verse\" for communities.<ref name=\":6\" /> In past workshops, the author has fostered the creation of toolkits for healing that she calls \u201cRecipe For\", in which participants reveal the key issues impacting their lives, and facilitators assist them to create a list of writing \"ingredients\" that they can use  independently to promote self-healing.<ref name=\":6\" /> In addition, she has conducted poetry and writing workshops with LGBTQ communities, undocumented immigrants, incarcerated people, women survivors of domestic abuse, and sex workers, among other marginalized groups, in which her purpose is to provide a platform to empower people to speak who often do not have the opportunity to have their voices heard.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Works by Trapeta B. Mayson==\n'''Books of Poetry'''\n\n*2018: ''She was once herself.'', OCLC [https://www.worldcat.org/title/she-was-once-herself/oclc/889180469 1055273795]\n*2008: ''Mocha melodies''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://writing.upenn.edu/wh/calendar/0504.html|title=WH Calendar: May 2004|website=writing.upenn.edu|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n*2004: ''By the roadside : for Liberian survivors of war.,'' OCLC [https://www.worldcat.org/title/by-the-roadside-for-liberian-survivors-of-war/oclc/60326929 1055273795]\n\n'''Contributor to Periodicals and Anthologies'''\n\n*2008: ''Letter to my sister''., The American Poetry Review, v37 n4 (20080701): 28, {{ISBN|9781944211615|}} OCLC [https://www.worldcat.org/title/letter-to-my-sister/oclc/5542763498 1049785850]\n\nMayson has also published in periodicals such as ''[[Aesthetica]] Magazine,The [[The American Poetry Review|American Poetry Review]],'' ''Aura, a [[University of Alabama]] Literary Journal''; ''[[Cave Canem Foundation|Cave Canem]]\u2019s literary review'', ''Epiphany Literary Journal, Margie: The American Journal of Poetry and Strong Medicine: American Journal of Poetry''; among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennbookcenter.com/event/poetry-reading-w-ir%C3%A8ne-mathieu-trapeta-mayson-raquel-salas-rivera|title=Poetry Reading w/ Ir\u00e8ne Mathieu, Trapeta Mayson, & Raquel Salas Rivera {{!}} Penn Book Center|website=www.pennbookcenter.com|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\nMayson was chosen as the fifth poet laureate of Philadelphia in 2019, under the auspices of the Free Library of Philadelphia. According to the selection committee, the poet was chosen because of her ability to balance a full-time poetic writing practice with participation in many local Philadelphia organizations.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to the poet, in her role she aspires to \u201ctouch base with social service agencies, particularly those pertaining to mental health, in [Philly\u2019s] communities.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> She considers the role to be \u201c...like a poetry ambassador for the city, ... Engaging communities, young people, people from all over the city, and engaging them in the creation of poetry, appreciation of poetry.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kywnewsradio.radio.com/articles/news/philly-s-new-poetry-ambassador-champions-creativity|title=Philly\u2019s new \u2018poetry ambassador\u2019 champions creativity, engagement|date=2019-12-12|website=KYW|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she was awarded an Aspen Words Emerging Writers fellowship from the [[Aspen Institute]].<ref name=\":7\" /> She also served as a juror for the 2019 Scholastic National Writing Awards from the [[Alliance for Young Artists & Writers]] in the category of Poetry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artandwriting.org/who-we-are/jurors/2019-national-writing-jurors/|title=2019 National Writing Jurors \u2013 Scholastic Art & Writing Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nThe author was nominated for a [[Pushcart Prize]] in 2016.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nFrom the Leeway Foundation, she received both an Art and Change Grant in 2014 and a Transformation Award in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leeway.org/artists/trapeta_b_mayson/|title=Trapeta B. Mayson|website=Leeway Foundation|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nThe poet was a 2002 fellow of the [[Pew Center for Arts & Heritage|Pew Center for Arts and Heritage]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewcenterarts.org/people/trapeta-b-mayson|title=Trapeta B. Mayson|last=admin|date=2016-11-30|website=The Pew Center for Arts & Heritage|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\nShe was a fellow of the [[Pennsylvania Council on the Arts|Pennsylvania Council of the Arts]] in both 2000 and 2004.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also==\n{{Portal|Liberia|Africa|Biography|Literature|Poetry}}\n*[[List of Liberian writers]]\n*[[List of African writers by country]]\n*[[Liberian Americans]]\n*[[List of alumni of Villanova University|List of Villanova University Alumni]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes\n|lcheading=\n|viaf=2201360}}\n\n* {{Official website|https://trapetamayson.com//}}\n\n=== Selected Poems ===\n\n*''[http://www.sablelitmag.org/trapeta-b-mayson/ Brother]''\n*''[http://www.sablelitmag.org/trapeta-b-mayson/ First Job Advice]''\n*[http://iiammoon.blogspot.com/2011/04/poetic-licensetrapeta-b-mayson.html ''I Long to Be'' (From Mocha Melodies)]\n*[https://www.personalizedmedicinebydesign.com/story-cure/ Stories Cure]\n\n=== Interviews ===\n\n*[https://www.theartblog.org/2019/12/getting-to-know-phillys-new-poet-laureate/ Getting to know Philly\u2019s new Poet Laureate - Trapeta Mayson, December 20,2019, Artblog]\n\n=== Performances and recordings ===\n\n*[https://kywnewsradio.radio.com/media/audio-channel/poems-by-philly-s-new-poet-laureate-trapeta-b-mayson 3 Poems by Trapeta Mayson - KYW Newsradio]\n*[http://www.sablelitmag.org/kadijasesay/blog/trapeta-mayson-march-14/ Cecilia Too Soon]\n*[https://www.nypl.org/audiovideo/celebrating-little-magazine-contemporary-america-0 Trapeta Mayson - An Evening with Epiphany Magazine]\n*[https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/love-jawns-a-mixtape/e/64767314 ''We Are All Trees Here'' (Love Jawns: A Mixtape - We Are All Enemies)]\n\n=== Exhibitions ===\n\n* [https://www.ifestudio3.com/public-art?lightbox=dataItem-j52xvmgk Read: a Pathway to Hope] (mural arts collaboration with artist Ife Nii Owoo)\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayson, Trapeta}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Temple University alumni]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College alumni]]\n[[Category:Villanova University alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberian women]]\n[[Category:Liberian writers]]\n[[Category:American social workers]]\n[[Category:Poets Laureate of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Municipal Poets Laureate in the United States]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:American spoken word artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pew Fellows in the Arts]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[