{"title_page": "Bania (caste)", "text_new": "{{short description|A sub-caste of Hindus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{About|the community of India|the Nepalese community|Bania (Newar caste)}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group= Bania\n|image = [[File:Banian.jpg|none|150px]]\n|image_caption = A Goan Bania, early 1880s\n|poptime =  \n|popplace = \n|langs = [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Marwari language|Marwari]], [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] Dialects of [[Marathi language|Marathi]] and [[Konkani language|Konkani]].<ref>''Gazetteer of the Union Territory Goa, Daman and Diu: district gazetter'' by Vithal Trimbak Gune, Goa, Daman and Diu (India). Gazetteer Dept, published by Gazetteer Dept., Govt. of the Union Territory of Goa, Daman and Diu, 1979</ref>\n|rels  = \n|related=\n}}\n\nThe '''Bania''' (otherwise known as '''Baniya''', '''Banija''', '''Vaniya''', '''Vani''', '''Vania''' and '''Vanya''') is an occupational community of [[merchant]]s, [[banker]]s, [[money-lender]]s, [[dealers in grains]] or [[dealers in spices|in spices]], and in modern times numerous commercial enterprises.\"The '''Bania''' are Vaishya according to the Hindu '''caste''' system and third in '''hierarchy''' below Rajputs and Brahmins but '''higher''' than all other '''castes'''.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peoplegroupsindia.com/profiles/bania/|title=Bania|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The term is used in a wider sense in [[Bengal]] than it is elsewhere in [[India]], where it is applied to specific [[caste]]s.<ref name=\"Schrader1997\">{{cite book|first=Heiko |last=Schrader|title=Changing financial landscapes in India and Indonesia: sociological aspects of monetization and market integration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8rf7nIIz8ikC&pg=PA68|accessdate=9 February 2012|year=1997|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster |isbn=978-3-8258-2641-3 |page=68}}</ref> In other words, it can be said that this caste mainly consists of businessmen. They are widespread all over India but are more in north as compared to south of India.\n\n==Etymologically related groups==\nIn [[West India|western India]] one merchant occupational group is called ''Vani'' or ''Vania''; in [[Bengal]] the term is applied to all people who are involved in moneylending and similar activities.<ref name=\"Schrader1997\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Magahi Sahu Vaishya]]\n* [[Vaishya]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |title= 'The Omnipresent Bania:' Rural Moneylenders in Nineteenth-Century Sind |first=David |last=Cheesman |journal=Modern Asian Studies |volume=16 |issue=3 |year=1982 |pages=445\u2013462 |jstor=312116 |doi=10.1017/s0026749x00015262}}\n*{{cite journal |title=The British and the Moneylender in Nineteenth-Century India |first=Thomas R. |last=Metcalf |authorlink=Thomas R. Metcalf |journal=The Journal of Modern History |volume=34 |issue=4 |date=December 1962 |pages=390\u2013397 |jstor=1880056 |doi=10.1086/239182}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Bania communities| ]]\n\n\n{{india-ethno-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A sub-caste of Hindus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{About|the community of India|the Nepalese community|Bania (Newar caste)}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group= Bania\n|image = [[File:Banian.jpg|none|150px]]\n|image_caption = A Goan Bania, early 1880s\n|poptime =  \n|popplace = \n|langs = [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Marwari language|Marwari]], [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] Dialects of [[Marathi language|Marathi]] and [[Konkani language|Konkani]].<ref>''Gazetteer of the Union Territory Goa, Daman and Diu: district gazetter'' by Vithal Trimbak Gune, Goa, Daman and Diu (India). Gazetteer Dept, published by Gazetteer Dept., Govt. of the Union Territory of Goa, Daman and Diu, 1979</ref>\n|rels  = \n|related=\n}}\n\nThe '''Bania''' (otherwise known as '''Baniya''', '''Banija''', '''Vaniya''', '''Vani''', '''Vania''' and '''Vanya''') is an occupational community of [[merchant]]s, [[banker]]s, [[money-lender]]s, [[dealers in grains]] or [[dealers in spices|in spices]], and in modern times numerous commercial enterprises. The term is used in a wider sense in [[Bengal]] than it is elsewhere in [[India]], where it is applied to specific [[caste]]s.<ref name=\"Schrader1997\">{{cite book|first=Heiko |last=Schrader|title=Changing financial landscapes in India and Indonesia: sociological aspects of monetization and market integration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8rf7nIIz8ikC&pg=PA68|accessdate=9 February 2012|year=1997|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster |isbn=978-3-8258-2641-3 |page=68}}</ref>\n\n==Etymologically related groups==\nIn [[West India|western India]] one merchant occupational group is called ''Vani'' or ''Vania''; in [[Bengal]] the term is applied to all people who are involved in moneylending and similar activities.<ref name=\"Schrader1997\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Magahi Sahu Vaishya]]\n* [[Vaishya]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |title= 'The Omnipresent Bania:' Rural Moneylenders in Nineteenth-Century Sind |first=David |last=Cheesman |journal=Modern Asian Studies |volume=16 |issue=3 |year=1982 |pages=445\u2013462 |jstor=312116 |doi=10.1017/s0026749x00015262}}\n*{{cite journal |title=The British and the Moneylender in Nineteenth-Century India |first=Thomas R. |last=Metcalf |authorlink=Thomas R. Metcalf |journal=The Journal of Modern History |volume=34 |issue=4 |date=December 1962 |pages=390\u2013397 |jstor=1880056 |doi=10.1086/239182}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Bania communities| ]]\n\n\n{{in